{"title_page": "BBC Light Programme", "text_new": "{{short description|Former BBC radio station}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox broadcasting network\n| name                 = BBC Light Programme\n| logo                 = \n| logo_size            = \n| logo_alt             = \n| logo caption         = \n| collapsible          = \n| image                = BBC Broadcasting House 532073098.jpg\n| image_size           = 220\n| image_alt            = A photograph of Broadcasting House showing the art deco styling of the main facade. made from Portland stone\n| caption              = The BBC Light Programme headquarters was at [[Broadcasting House]] in [[London]].\n| type                 = \n| country              = United Kingdom\n| motto                = \n| slogan               = \n| radiotransmitters    = \n| license_area         = \n| headquarters         = [[Broadcasting House]], London, UK\n| broadcast_area       = \n| area                 = \n| nation               = \n| regions              = \n| erp                  = \n| owner                = [[BBC]]\n| key_people           = \n| launch_date          = {{Start date|1945|07|29|df=y}}\n| dissolved            = {{End date|1967|09|29|df=y}}\n| callsigns            = \n| callsign_meaning     = \n| language             = English\n| replaced             = [[BBC General Forces Programme]]\n| replaced_by          = [[BBC Radio 2]]\n| footnotes            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Light Programme''' was a [[BBC]] radio station which broadcast chiefly mainstream [[light entertainment]] and [[light music|music]] from 1945 until 1967, when it was replaced by [[BBC Radio 2]]. It opened on 29 July 1945, taking over the [[longwave]] frequency which had earlier been used \u2013 prior to the outbreak of the [[Second World War]] in September 1939 \u2013 by the [[BBC National Programme]].\n\nThe service was intended as a domestic replacement for the [[World War II|wartime]] [[BBC General Forces Programme]] which had proved popular with civilian audiences in Britain as well as members of the armed forces.\n\n==History==\n\nThe longwave signal on 200 kHz/1500 metres was transmitted from [[Droitwich transmitting station|Droitwich]] in the [[English Midlands|Midlands]] (as it still is today for [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]], although adjusted slightly to 198 kHz/1515 metres in 1988), and gave fairly good coverage of most of the [[United Kingdom]], although a number of low-power mediumwave transmitters (using 1214 kHz/247 metres) were added later to fill in local blank spots. Over the course of the 1950s and 1960s, the Light Programme (along with the BBC's two other national programmes, the [[BBC Home Service|Home Service]] and the [[BBC Third Programme|Third Programme]]) gradually became available on what was known at the time as VHF, as the BBC developed a network of local [[Frequency modulation|FM]] transmitters.\n\nFrom its first day of broadcasting in 1945 until Monday 2 September 1957, the Light Programme would be on the air from 9&nbsp;am until midnight each day, apart from Sundays when it would come on the air at 8&nbsp;am. From Monday 2 September 1957, the Light Programme's broadcasting hours would start to increase, with a new early morning start time of 7&nbsp;am, later moving to 6:30&nbsp;a.m. from Monday 29 September 1958. In 1964 broadcasting hours were increased even more, with a new morning start time of 5:30&nbsp;am from Monday 31 August 1964. Up until September 1964, the Light Programme would always end its broadcasting day at midnight, however this changed on Sunday 27 September 1964, when a new closedown time of 2:02&nbsp;a.m. was introduced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/light/1964-09-26|title=Light Programme - 26 September 1964 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/light/1957-09-02|title=Light Programme - 2 September 1957 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/light/1958-09-29|title=Light Programme - 29 September 1958 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/light/1945-07-29|title=Light Programme - 29 July 1945 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe Light Programme closed down for the last time at 2:02&nbsp;am on Friday 29 September 1967. At 5:30&nbsp;a.m. on Saturday 30 September 1967 it was replaced by [[BBC Radio 2]] on its [[longwave]] frequency and [[VHF]]. \n\nThe long-running soap opera ''[[The Archers]]'' was first heard nationally on the Light Programme, on 1 January 1951,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4703411/William-Smethurst-the-man-who-turned-The-Archers-into-a-cult.html|title=William Smethurst: the man who turned The Archers into a cult|first=Gillian|last=Reynolds|date=24 August 1996|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> although a week-long pilot version had been broadcast on the [[BBC Home Service|Midlands Home Service]] in 1950.\n\n==Notable programmes==\n{{div col}}\n*''[[The Al Read Show]]''\n*''[[Appointment with Fear (radio)|Appointment with Fear]]''\n*''[[The Archers]]''\n*''[[Beyond Our Ken]]''\n*''[[Billy Cotton Band Show|The Billy Cotton Band Show]]''\n*''[[Breakfast Special]]''\n*''[[Children's Favourites]]''\n*''[[The Clitheroe Kid]]''\n*''[[Dick Barton \u2013 Special Agent]]''\n*''[[Does The Team Think?]]''\n*''[[Educating Archie]]''\n*''[[Family Favourites]]''\n*''[[Friday Night Is Music Night]]''\n*''[[The Goon Show]]'' (repeats from the [[BBC Home Service]])\n*''[[Hancock's Half Hour]]''\n*''[[Have a Go!]]''\n*''[[Housewives' Choice]]''\n*''[[Ignorance Is Bliss (radio programme)|Ignorance is Bliss]]''\n*''[[I'm Sorry, I'll Read That Again]]''\n*''[[It's That Man Again|ITMA]]''  (repeats from the BBC Home Service)\n*''[[Journey into Space]]''\n*''[[Junior Choice|Children's Favourites]]''\n*''[[Life with the Lyons]]''\n*''[[Listen with Mother]]''\n*''[[Meet the Huggetts]]''\n*''[[Movie-Go-Round]]''\n*''[[Mrs Dale's Diary]]''\n*''[[Much Binding in the Marsh]]''\n*''[[Music While You Work]]''\n*''[[The Navy Lark]]''\n*''[[Orbiter X]]''\n*''[[Pick of the Pops]]''\n*''[[Radio Newsreel]]''\n*''[[Ray's a Laugh]]''\n*''Richard Attenborough's Record Rendezvous''\n*''[[Riders of the Range (radio programme)|Riders of the Range]]''\n*''[[Round the Horne]]''\n*''[[Roundabout (radio programme)|Roundabout]]''\n*''[[Shadow of Sumuru (radio programme)|Shadow of Sumuru]]''\n*''[[The Showband Show]]''\n*''[[Sing Something Simple]]''\n*''[[The Slide]]''\n*''[[Sports Report]]''\n*''[[Take It From Here]]''\n*''[[Variety Bandbox]]''\n*''[[Waterlogged Spa]]''\n*''[[Welsh Rarebit (radio programme)|Welsh Rarebit]]''\n*''[[Woman's Hour]]''\n*''[[Workers' Playtime (radio programme)|Workers' Playtime]]'' (BBC Home Service until September 1957)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Presenters==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n{{div col}}\n*[[Barry Alldis]]\n*[[Marjorie Anderson]]\n*[[Richard Attenborough]]<ref>https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/656f9afff7134c55a271f709472f2248</ref>\n*[[Tim Brinton]]\n*[[Michael Brooke]]\n*[[Desmond Carrington]]\n*[[Sam Costa]]\n*[[Bill Crozier (broadcaster)|Bill Crozier]]\n*[[Alan Dell]]\n*[[Robert Dougall]]\n*[[David Dunhill]]\n*[[John Churchill Dunn|John Dunn]]\n*[[Don Durbridge]]\n*[[Franklin Engelmann]]\n*[[Peter Fettes]]\n*[[Alan Freeman]]\n*[[Tony Blackburn]]\n*[[Annie Nightingale]]\n*[[Tim Gudgin]]\n*[[Peter Haigh]]\n*[[Colin Hamilton (broadcaster)|Colin Hamilton]]\n*[[Paul Hollingdale]]\n*[[David Jacobs (broadcaster)|David Jacobs]]\n*[[Brian Matthew]]\n*[[Jean Metcalfe]]\n*[[Roger Moffat]]\n*[[Pete Murray (disc jockey)|Pete Murray]]\n*[[Phillip Slessor]]\n*[[Douglas Smith (broadcaster)|Douglas Smith]]\n*[[Ken Sykora]]\n*[[David Symonds]]\n*[[John Webster (BBC)|John Webster]]\n*[[Roy Williams (broadcaster)|Roy Williams]]\n*[[Bruce Wyndham]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.radiorewind.co.uk/radio2/light_programme_page.htm Radio Rewind \u2013 The 1500m Light Programme]\n\n{{Former national BBC radio stations}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct BBC national radio stations|Light Programme, BBC]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1945]]\n[[Category:Radio stations disestablished in 1967]]\n[[Category:1945 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1967 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:BBC Light Programme| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former BBC radio station}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox broadcasting network\n| name                 = BBC Light Programme\n| logo                 = \n| logo_size            = \n| logo_alt             = \n| logo caption         = \n| collapsible          = \n| image                = BBC Broadcasting House 532073098.jpg\n| image_size           = 220\n| image_alt            = A photograph of Broadcasting House showing the art deco styling of the main facade. made from Portland stone\n| caption              = The BBC Light Programme headquarters was at [[Broadcasting House]] in [[London]]\n| type                 = \n| country              = United Kingdom\n| motto                = \n| slogan               = \n| radiotransmitters    = \n| license_area         = \n| headquarters         = [[Broadcasting House]], London, UK\n| broadcast_area       = \n| area                 = \n| nation               = \n| regions              = \n| erp                  = \n| owner                = [[BBC]]\n| key_people           = \n| launch_date          = {{Start date|1945|07|29|df=y}}\n| dissolved            = {{End date|1967|09|29|df=y}}\n| callsigns            = \n| callsign_meaning     = \n| language             = English\n| replaced             = [[BBC General Forces Programme]]\n| replaced_by          = [[BBC Radio 2]]\n| footnotes            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Light Programme''' was a [[BBC]] radio station which broadcast chiefly mainstream [[light entertainment]] and [[light music|music]] from 1945 until 1967, when it was replaced by [[BBC Radio 2]]. It opened on 29 July 1945, taking over the [[longwave]] frequency which had earlier been used \u2013 prior to the outbreak of the [[Second World War]] in September 1939 \u2013 by the [[BBC National Programme]].\n\nThe service was intended as a domestic replacement for the [[World War II|wartime]] [[BBC General Forces Programme]] which had proved popular with civilian audiences in Britain as well as members of the armed forces.\n\n==History==\n\nThe longwave signal on 200 kHz/1500 metres was transmitted from [[Droitwich transmitting station|Droitwich]] in the [[English Midlands|Midlands]] (as it still is today for [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]], although adjusted slightly to 198 kHz/1515 metres in 1988), and gave fairly good coverage of most of the [[United Kingdom]], although a number of low-power mediumwave transmitters (using 1214 kHz/247 metres) were added later to fill in local blank spots. Over the course of the 1950s and 1960s, the Light Programme (along with the BBC's two other national programmes, the [[BBC Home Service|Home Service]] and the [[BBC Third Programme|Third Programme]]) gradually became available on what was known at the time as VHF, as the BBC developed a network of local [[Frequency modulation|FM]] transmitters.\n\nFrom its first day of broadcasting in 1945 until Monday 2 September 1957, the Light Programme would be on the air from 9&nbsp;am until midnight each day, apart from Sundays when it would come on the air at 8&nbsp;am. From Monday 2 September 1957, the Light Programme's broadcasting hours would start to increase, with a new early morning start time of 7&nbsp;am, later moving to 6:30&nbsp;a.m. from Monday 29 September 1958. In 1964 broadcasting hours were increased even more, with a new morning start time of 5:30&nbsp;am from Monday 31 August 1964. Up until September 1964, the Light Programme would always end its broadcasting day at midnight, however this changed on Sunday 27 September 1964, when a new closedown time of 2:02&nbsp;a.m. was introduced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/light/1964-09-26|title=Light Programme - 26 September 1964 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/light/1957-09-02|title=Light Programme - 2 September 1957 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/light/1958-09-29|title=Light Programme - 29 September 1958 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/light/1945-07-29|title=Light Programme - 29 July 1945 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe Light Programme closed down for the last time at 2:02&nbsp;am on Friday 29 September 1967. At 5:30&nbsp;a.m. on Saturday 30 September 1967 it was replaced by [[BBC Radio 2]] on its [[longwave]] frequency and [[VHF]]. \n\nThe long-running soap opera ''[[The Archers]]'' was first heard nationally on the Light Programme, on 1 January 1951,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4703411/William-Smethurst-the-man-who-turned-The-Archers-into-a-cult.html|title=William Smethurst: the man who turned The Archers into a cult|first=Gillian|last=Reynolds|date=24 August 1996|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> although a week-long pilot version had been broadcast on the [[BBC Home Service|Midlands Home Service]] in 1950.\n\n==Notable programmes==\n{{div col}}\n*''[[The Al Read Show]]''\n*''[[Appointment with Fear (radio)|Appointment with Fear]]''\n*''[[The Archers]]''\n*''[[Beyond Our Ken]]''\n*''[[Billy Cotton Band Show|The Billy Cotton Band Show]]''\n*''[[Breakfast Special]]''\n*''[[Children's Favourites]]''\n*''[[The Clitheroe Kid]]''\n*''[[Dick Barton \u2013 Special Agent]]''\n*''[[Does The Team Think?]]''\n*''[[Educating Archie]]''\n*''[[Family Favourites]]''\n*''[[Friday Night Is Music Night]]''\n*''[[The Goon Show]]'' (repeats from the [[BBC Home Service]])\n*''[[Hancock's Half Hour]]''\n*''[[Have a Go!]]''\n*''[[Housewives' Choice]]''\n*''[[Ignorance Is Bliss (radio programme)|Ignorance is Bliss]]''\n*''[[I'm Sorry, I'll Read That Again]]''\n*''[[It's That Man Again|ITMA]]''  (repeats from the BBC Home Service)\n*''[[Journey into Space]]''\n*''[[Junior Choice|Children's Favourites]]''\n*''[[Life with the Lyons]]''\n*''[[Listen with Mother]]''\n*''[[Meet the Huggetts]]''\n*''[[Movie-Go-Round]]''\n*''[[Mrs Dale's Diary]]''\n*''[[Much Binding in the Marsh]]''\n*''[[Music While You Work]]''\n*''[[The Navy Lark]]''\n*''[[Orbiter X]]''\n*''[[Pick of the Pops]]''\n*''[[Radio Newsreel]]''\n*''[[Ray's a Laugh]]''\n*''Richard Attenborough's Record Rendezvous''\n*''[[Riders of the Range (radio programme)|Riders of the Range]]''\n*''[[Round the Horne]]''\n*''[[Roundabout (radio programme)|Roundabout]]''\n*''[[Shadow of Sumuru (radio programme)|Shadow of Sumuru]]''\n*''[[The Showband Show]]''\n*''[[Sing Something Simple]]''\n*''[[The Slide]]''\n*''[[Sports Report]]''\n*''[[Take It From Here]]''\n*''[[Variety Bandbox]]''\n*''[[Waterlogged Spa]]''\n*''[[Welsh Rarebit (radio programme)|Welsh Rarebit]]''\n*''[[Woman's Hour]]''\n*''[[Workers' Playtime (radio programme)|Workers' Playtime]]'' (BBC Home Service until September 1957)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Presenters==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n{{div col}}\n*[[Barry Alldis]]\n*[[Marjorie Anderson]]\n*[[Richard Attenborough]]<ref>https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/656f9afff7134c55a271f709472f2248</ref>\n*[[Tim Brinton]]\n*[[Michael Brooke]]\n*[[Desmond Carrington]]\n*[[Sam Costa]]\n*[[Bill Crozier (broadcaster)|Bill Crozier]]\n*[[Alan Dell]]\n*[[Robert Dougall]]\n*[[David Dunhill]]\n*[[John Churchill Dunn|John Dunn]]\n*[[Don Durbridge]]\n*[[Franklin Engelmann]]\n*[[Peter Fettes]]\n*[[Alan Freeman]]\n*[[Tony Blackburn]]\n*[[Annie Nightingale]]\n*[[Tim Gudgin]]\n*[[Peter Haigh]]\n*[[Colin Hamilton (broadcaster)|Colin Hamilton]]\n*[[Paul Hollingdale]]\n*[[David Jacobs (broadcaster)|David Jacobs]]\n*[[Brian Matthew]]\n*[[Jean Metcalfe]]\n*[[Roger Moffat]]\n*[[Pete Murray (disc jockey)|Pete Murray]]\n*[[Phillip Slessor]]\n*[[Douglas Smith (broadcaster)|Douglas Smith]]\n*[[Ken Sykora]]\n*[[David Symonds]]\n*[[John Webster (BBC)|John Webster]]\n*[[Roy Williams (broadcaster)|Roy Williams]]\n*[[Bruce Wyndham]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.radiorewind.co.uk/radio2/light_programme_page.htm Radio Rewind \u2013 The 1500m Light Programme]\n\n{{Former national BBC radio stations}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct BBC national radio stations|Light Programme, BBC]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1945]]\n[[Category:Radio stations disestablished in 1967]]\n[[Category:1945 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1967 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:BBC Light Programme| ]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "Caption punctuation adjustment, per WP:CAPFRAG", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BBC_Light_Programme"}
{"title_page": "Gaten Matarazzo", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor and singer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gaten Matarazzo\n| image              = File:Gaten Matarazzo by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Matarazzo at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name         = Gaetano John Matarazzo III\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|2002|9|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Connecticut, United States]]<ref>https://bestofnj.com/features/entertainment/things-didnt-know-gaten-matarazzo-stranger-things/</ref>\n| occupation         = Actor, singer\n| years_active       = 2011\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Gaetano John''' \"'''Gaten'''\" '''Matarazzo III'''<ref>Matarzzo at {{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CEMeDw7dCb4|title=Stranger Things' Gaten Matarazzo Goes Undercover on Reddit, YouTube and Twitter|work=[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]|date= July 1, 2019|accessdate= July 1, 2019|medium=www.youtube.com|time=00:46|quote=It's actually Gaetano John Matarazzo III.}}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|e\u026a|t|\u0259n|_|\u02cc|m|\u00e6|t|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u00e6|z|o\u028a}}; {{IPA-it|\u0261ae\u02c8ta\u02d0no mata\u02c8rattso|lang}}; born September 8, 2002)<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/09/08/UPI-Almanac-for-Sunday-Sept-8-2019/2621567647013/|title= UPI Almanac for Sunday, Sept. 8, 2019|agency= [[United Press International]] | date= September 8, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2020 |archivedate= September 9, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190909031013/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/09/08/UPI-Almanac-for-Sunday-Sept-8-2019/2621567647013/|url-status=live|quote=\u2026actor Gaten Matarazzo in 2002 (age 17)}}</ref> is an American actor and singer. He began his career on the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] stage as Benjamin in ''[[Priscilla, Queen of the Desert (musical)|Priscilla, Queen of the Desert]]'' and as [[Gavroche]] in ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.playbill.com/personlistpage/person-list?production=00000150-aea8-d936-a7fd-eefc733d0003&type=op#oc|title=Les Mis\u00e9rables|magazine=[[Playbill]]|accessdate=August 18, 2016}}</ref> He stars as [[Dustin Henderson]] in the [[Netflix]] science-fiction-horror drama series ''[[Stranger Things]],'' and hosts the Netflix show ''[[Prank Encounters]]''. \n\n==Early life==\nMatarazzo was born in [[Connecticut]], to Gaetano and [[Heather Matarazzo]], but raised in [[ Little Egg Harbor Township, New Jersey]], and he attended Pinelands Regional High School in [[Tuckerton, New Jersey]].<ref name=PromPhotos>{{cite news|url= https://www.nj.com/entertainment/2019/05/nj-stranger-things-star-gaten-matarazzo-shows-off-prom-photos.html|title=N.J. 'Stranger Things' star Gaten Matarazzo shows off prom photos|date=May 6, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2020|first=Amy|last= Kuperinsky|publisher=[[New Jersey Advance Media]]|archivedate=January 30, 2020|archiveurl=http://archive.is/Ygf8J|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.j-14.com/posts/gaten-matarazzo-heather-matarazzo-150838/|title=Gaten Matarazzo and Heather Matarazzo: Are They Related?|date=2018-01-26|website=J-14|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref> He has two siblings, an older sister Sabrina and a younger brother Carmen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looper.com/156982/the-untold-truth-of-gaten-matarazzo/|title=The untold truth of Gaten Matarazzo|last=Santilli|first=Morgana|date=2019-06-28|website=Looper.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMatarazzo is of [[Italians|Italian]] descent.<ref>[http://247.libero.it/lfocus/39105018/1/gaten-matarazzo-il-dustin-di-stranger-things-ha-famiglia-originaria-di-avellino/]</ref><ref>[http://www.ansa.it/sito/notizie/cultura/tv/2019/07/05/stranger-things-amicizia-batte-paura_ac7df6be-2e17-41ce-8ffc-9d7ee816074d.html]</ref>\n\nMatarazzo was born with [[cleidocranial dysostosis]], which he has spoken openly about, even documenting one of his surgeries, during which 14 [[supernumary teeth]] were removed, on [[Instagram]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/02/02/stranger-things-star-gaten-matarazzo-gives-thumbs-successful-fourth-surgery-fourth-surgery-rare-bone-condition-complete-success-12168587/|title=Stranger Things star Gaten Matarazzo's surgery is a complete success|date=2020-02-02|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ro|first=Crystal|url=http://hellogiggles.com/dustin-stranger-things-loves-showing-off-fake-teeth-real-life-obviously-adorable|title=Dustin from \"Stranger Things\" loves showing off his fake teeth in real life, and obviously it's adorable|publisher=HelloGiggles.com|date=August 5, 2016}}</ref> After he was cast in ''[[Stranger Things]]'' as [[Dustin Henderson]], the character's background was modified to have the condition as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/article/20121-dustin-stranger-things-missing-teeth|title=Stranger Things: What Happened to Gaten Matarazzo's Teeth?|website=Inverse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> He uses [[dentures]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/09/28/gaten-matarazzo-disorder_n_12232838.html|title=Gaten Matarazzo Of 'Stranger Things' Talks About His Genetic Disorder|magazine=[[Huffington Post]]|date=September 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe is a vegetarian.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bestofnj.com/features/entertainment/things-didnt-know-gaten-matarazzo-stranger-things/|title=9 Things You Didn't Know About Gaten Matarazzo (Stranger Things)|date=2017-10-24|website=Best of NJ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nMatarazzo uses his platform to raise awareness of CCD and fundraise for CCD Smiles, an organization that helps cover costs of oral surgeries for people with CCD. Matarazzo has also started a line of T-shirts whose proceeds will go to CCD Smiles. On his social media sites, Matarazzo tells followers how to donate to CCD Smiles and promotes events he will participate in. In November 2017, his sister started a Facebook campaign to raise money for the organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://startsomegood.com/ccd-smiles|title=Donate to CCD Smiles!|publisher=StartSomeGood|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=46188187&nid=148&title=stranger-things-star-brings-smiles-to-utahns-with-rare-genetic-disorder|title='Stranger Things' star brings smiles to Utahns with rare genetic disorder|publisher=[[KSL-TV]]|location=Salt Lake City, Utah|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film and television \n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Blacklist (TV series)|The Blacklist]]''\n| Finn\n| TV series (Episode: \"The Kenyon Family (No. 71)\")\n|-\n| 2016\u2013present\n| ''[[Stranger Things]]''\n| [[Dustin Henderson]]\n|TV series; main role\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Ridiculousness (TV series)|Ridiculousness]]''\n| Himself\n| TV series (Episode: \"Scarediculousness\")\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Lip Sync Battle]]''\n| Himself\n| TV series (Episode: \"The Cast of ''Stranger Things''\")\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Angry Birds Movie 2]]''\n| Bubba\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Prank Encounters]]''\n| Himself / Host\n| TV series<ref>{{cite web | last=Squires | first=John | title=[Trailer] Gaten Matarazzo Hosts New Scare-Based Prank Show \"Prank Encounters\" for Netflix | website=Bloody Disgusting | date=October 10, 2019 | url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/tv/3588389/trailer-gaten-matarazzo-hosts-new-scare-based-prank-show-prank-encounters-netflix/ | access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2017\n| \"[[Swish Swish]]\"\n| [[Katy Perry]] <small>(feat. [[Nicki Minaj]])</small><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Bell|first1=Sadie|title=Here Are All the Cameos From Katy Perry's 'Swish Swish' Music Video