{"title_page": "Gerard Hogan", "text_new": "{{Infobox judge\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable|The Hon. Mr. Justice]]\n| name             = Gerard Hogan\n| image            =\n| office           = Advocate General of the [[European Court of Justice]]\n| president        = [[Koen Lenaerts]]\n| term_start       = 8 October 2018\n| term_end         = \n| predecessor      = [[Melchior Wathelet]]\n| nominator       = [[Government of the 32nd D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| successor        =\n| office1          = Judge of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]]\n| term_start1      = 24 October 2014\n| term_end1        = 7 October 2018\n| nominator1       = [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer1       = [[Michael D. Higgins]]\n| office2          = Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start2      = 11 November 2010\n| term_end2        = 24 October 2014\n| nominator2       = [[Government of the 30th D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer2       = [[Mary McAleese]]\n| birth_name       = Gerard William Augustine Hogan\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1958|8|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Carrick-on-Suir]], [[County Tipperary]], Ireland\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = {{Ubl|[[University College Dublin]]|[[University of Pennsylvania]]|[[Trinity College Dublin]]|[[King's Inns]]}}\n| signature        =\n|}}\n'''Gerard William Augustine Hogan'''<ref>{{cite web |title=University and College Officers |url=https://www.tcd.ie/assets/documents/calendar/part1_university_and_college_officers.pdf |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> (born 13 August 1958) is an Irish lawyer and academic is currently an [[Advocate General]] of the [[European Court of Justice]]. He was formerly a Judge of the Irish [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]] and the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]].\n\n== Early career ==\nHogan is from [[Carrick-on-Suir]], [[County Tipperary]]. His father was the deputy principal of [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]] secondary school in the town.<ref name=\"Tipperary Live 2018\">{{cite news |title=Tipperary judge nominated to European Court of Justice |url=https://www.tipperarylive.ie/news/carrick-on-suir/314496/tipperary-judge-nominated-to-european-court-of-justice.html |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=www.tipperarylive.ie}}</ref> He was educated at [[University College Dublin]], the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and the [[King's Inns]]. He received a PhD in law from [[Trinity College Dublin]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Curia Bio\">{{cite web |title=CURIA - Gerard Hogan |url=https://curia.europa.eu/jcms/jcms/p1_1347854/en/ |website=curia.europa.eu |accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> He was called to the Bar in 1984 and became a [[Senior Counsel]] in 1997. He acted for the [[Attorney General of Ireland]] in a [[Council of State (Ireland)#Referring of bills|reference]] made by President [[Mary Robinson]] under Article 26 of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] to the Supreme Court regarding the Employment Equality Bill of 1997.<ref>{{cite news |title=Equal Status Bill hearing is fixed for next month |work=The Irish Times |date=13 May 1997}}</ref> He appeared again for the Attorney General (with [[Dermot Gleeson]] and [[Paul Gallagher (barrister)|Paul Gallagher]]) in another reference made by President [[Mary McAleese]] regarding the Health (Amendment) (No. 2) Bill 2004.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=In the matter of Article 26 of the Constitution and in the matter of the Health (Amendment) (No. 2) Bill 2004 |reporter=[2005] IESC 7 |court=Supreme Court of Ireland |date=16 February 2005 |url=http://www.supremecourt.ie/supremecourt/sclibrary3.nsf/(WebFiles)/8656ED6FCD1EAD03802575F300335737/$FILE/Health_%5B2005%5D%201%20IR%20105.htm |access-date=25 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nHe was a law lecturer and fellow in Trinity College Dublin from 1982 to 2007.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.taoiseach.gov.ie/eng/News/Government_Press_Releases/Appointments_to_the_Court_of_Appeal.html | work=Department of the Taoiseach| title=Appointments to the Court of Appeal | date=29 October 2014}}</ref> He is regarded as \"one of the foremost constitutional and administrative lawyers in Ireland\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://humanrights.ie/announcements/gerard-hogan-sc-nominated-to-high-court/ | work=Human Rights in Ireland www.humanrights.ie| title=Gerard Hogan SC nominated to High Court | date=21 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305014711/http://www.humanrights.ie/announcements/gerard-hogan-sc-nominated-to-high-court/ |archive-date=2017-03-05 |}}</ref> He is the co-author of '' Administrative Law in Ireland'' and ''JM Kelly: The Irish Constitution'', the core Irish legal texts in Irish administrative and constitutional law respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gerard Hogan |url=https://www.law.upenn.edu/live/profiles/1122-gerard-hogan/profiles/international-alumni-spotlight |website=www.law.upenn.edu |accessdate=9 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> He has also written a text on political violence and a book where he chronicled the origins of the [[Constitution of Ireland]].<ref name=\"Aarhus Law\">{{cite web |title=Lecture by Advocate General Gerard Hogan of the Court of Justice of the European Union |url=https://law.au.dk/en/current/events/event/artikel/foredrag-af-eu-domstolens-generaladvokat-gerard-hogan/ |website=law.au.dk |accessdate=9 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first barrister to appear in an Irish court without a wig, following the enactment of the Courts and Court Officers Act 1995.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man shot in house at Tallaght |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/man-shot-in-house-at-tallaght-1.21028 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=12 January 1996 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Judicial career ==\n=== High Court ===\nHe was appointed a Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] in 2010. Soon after his appointment, he held an emergency hearing in his home regarding a blood transfusion for a sick baby.<ref name=\"Sunday Independent 2013\">{{cite news |title='Brains of the bench' Hogan has been a champion for the rights of citizens |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/brains-of-the-bench-hogan-has-been-a-champion-for-the-rights-of-citizens-29453805.html |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=Independent.ie |date=28 July 2013 |language=en}}</ref> He was one of three judges who heard a case taken by Marie Fleming, seeking a [[right to die]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1=Valerie |title=Appalling ordeal of an extraordinary woman |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/appalling-ordeal-of-an-extraordinary-woman-29859091.html |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=Independent.ie |language=en}}</ref> His reference to the [[European Court of Justice]] in 2014 regarding the [[International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles]], resulted in a declaration by the Grand Chamber that the Safe Harbour Decision was invalid.<ref name=\"Aarhus Law\" />\n\n=== Court of Appeal ===\nHe subsequently became as a Judge of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]] upon its establishment in October 2014.<ref name=\"IT Sept 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Leahy |first1=Pat |title=Irish judge takes up key role in European Court of Justice |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/irish-judge-takes-up-key-role-in-european-court-of-justice-1.3627370 |work=The Irish Times |date=12 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocate General ===\nIn May 2018, he was nominated by the [[Government of Ireland]] for appointment as the [[Advocate General]] to the [[European Court of Justice]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/court-of-appeal-judge-nominated-to-european-court-of-justice-1.3507592 | work=Irish Times| title=Court of Appeal judge nominated to European Court of Justice | date=25 May 2018}}</ref> His term began in October 2018 and will expire in October 2024.<ref name=\"Tipperary Live 2018\" /> \n\nIn one of his first opinions, on a reference from the French [[Conseil d'\u00c9tat (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]], he found that Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 25 October 2011 requires that products originating from [[Israeli-occupied territories]] should indicate if these products come from such a territory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adviser to EU court says settlement goods should be labeled |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/adviser-to-eu-court-says-settlement-goods-should-be-labeled/ |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=www.timesofisrael.com}}</ref> His opinion was followed by the Court of Justice.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crisp |first1=James |title=EU's top court rules food from Israeli settlements must carry special label |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/12/eus-top-court-rules-food-israeli-settlements-must-carry-special/ |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hogan, Gerard}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Advocates General of the European Court of Justice]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Court of Appeal (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:High Court judges (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox judge\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable|The Hon. Mr. Justice]]\n| name             = Gerard Hogan\n| image            =\n| office           = Advocate General of the [[European Court of Justice]]\n| president        = [[Koen Lenaerts]]\n| term_start       = 8 October 2018\n| term_end         = \n| predecessor      = [[Melchior Wathelet]]\n| nominator       = [[Government of the 32nd D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| successor        =\n| office1          = Judge of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]]\n| term_start1      = 24 October 2014\n| term_end1        = 7 October 2018\n| nominator1       = [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer1       = [[Michael D. Higgins]]\n| office2          = Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start2      = 11 November 2010\n| term_end2        = 24 October 2014\n| nominator2       = [[Government of the 30th D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer2       = [[Mary McAleese]]\n| birth_name       = Gerard William Augustine Hogan\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1958|8|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Carrick-on-Suir]], [[County Tipperary]], Ireland\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = {{Ubl|[[University College Dublin]]|[[University of Pennsylvania]]|[[Trinity College Dublin]]|[[King's Inns]]}}\n| signature        =\n|}}\n'''Gerard William Augustine Hogan'''<ref>{{cite web |title=University and College Officers |url=https://www.tcd.ie/assets/documents/calendar/part1_university_and_college_officers.pdf |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> (born 13 August 1958) is an Irish lawyer and academic is currently an [[Advocate General]] of the [[European Court of Justice]]. He was formerly a Judge of the Irish [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]] and the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]].\n\n== Early career ==\nHogan is from [[Carrick-on-Suir]], [[County Tipperary]]. His father was the deputy principal of [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]] secondary school in the town.<ref name=\"Tipperary Live 2018\">{{cite news |title=Tipperary judge nominated to European Court of Justice |url=https://www.tipperarylive.ie/news/carrick-on-suir/314496/tipperary-judge-nominated-to-european-court-of-justice.html |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=www.tipperarylive.ie}}</ref> He was educated at [[University College Dublin]], the [[University of Pennsylvania]], and the [[King's Inns]]. He received a PhD in law from [[Trinity College Dublin]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Curia Bio\">{{cite web |title=CURIA - Gerard Hogan |url=https://curia.europa.eu/jcms/jcms/p1_1347854/en/ |website=curia.europa.eu |accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> He was called to the Bar in 1984 and became a [[Senior Counsel]] in 1997. He acted for the [[Attorney General of Ireland]] in a [[Council of State (Ireland)#Referring of bills|reference]] made by President [[Mary Robinson]] under Article 26 of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] to the Supreme Court regarding the Employment Equality Bill of 1997.<ref>{{cite news |title=Equal Status Bill hearing is fixed for next month |work=The Irish Times |date=13 May 1997}}</ref> He appeared again for the Attorney General (with [[Dermot Gleeson]] and [[Paul Gallagher (barrister)|Paul Gallagher]]) in another reference made by President [[Mary McAleese]] regarding the Health (Amendment) (No. 2) Bill 2004.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=In the matter of Article 26 of the Constitution and in the matter of the Health (Amendment) (No. 2) Bill 2004 |reporter=[2005] IESC 7 |court=Supreme Court of Ireland |date=16 February 2005 |url=http://www.supremecourt.ie/supremecourt/sclibrary3.nsf/(WebFiles)/8656ED6FCD1EAD03802575F300335737/$FILE/Health_%5B2005%5D%201%20IR%20105.htm |access-date=25 April 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nHe was a law lecturer and fellow in Trinity College Dublin from 1982 to 2007.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.taoiseach.gov.ie/eng/News/Government_Press_Releases/Appointments_to_the_Court_of_Appeal.html | work=Department of the Taoiseach| title=Appointments to the Court of Appeal | date=29 October 2014}}</ref> He is regarded as \"one of the foremost constitutional and administrative lawyers in Ireland\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://humanrights.ie/announcements/gerard-hogan-sc-nominated-to-high-court/ | work=Human Rights in Ireland www.humanrights.ie| title=Gerard Hogan SC nominated to High Court | date=21 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305014711/http://www.humanrights.ie/announcements/gerard-hogan-sc-nominated-to-high-court/ |archive-date=2017-03-05 |}}</ref> He is the co-author of '' Administrative Law in Ireland'' and ''JM Kelly: The Irish Constitution'', the core Irish legal texts in Irish administrative and constitutional law respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gerard Hogan |url=https://www.law.upenn.edu/live/profiles/1122-gerard-hogan/profiles/international-alumni-spotlight |website=www.law.upenn.edu |accessdate=9 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> He has also written a text on political violence and a book where he chronicled the origins of the [[Constitution of Ireland]].<ref name=\"Aarhus Law\">{{cite web |title=Lecture by Advocate General Gerard Hogan of the Court of Justice of the European Union |url=https://law.au.dk/en/current/events/event/artikel/foredrag-af-eu-domstolens-generaladvokat-gerard-hogan/ |website=law.au.dk |accessdate=9 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first barrister to appear in an Irish court without a wig, following the enactment of the Courts and Court Officers Act 1995.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man shot in house at Tallaght |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/man-shot-in-house-at-tallaght-1.21028 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=12 January 1996 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Judicial career ==\nHe was appointed a Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] in 2010. Soon after his appointment, he held an emergency hearing in his home regarding a blood transfusion for a sick baby.<ref name=\"Sunday Independent 2013\">{{cite news |title='Brains of the bench' Hogan has been a champion for the rights of citizens |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/brains-of-the-bench-hogan-has-been-a-champion-for-the-rights-of-citizens-29453805.html |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=Independent.ie |date=28 July 2013 |language=en}}</ref> He was one of three judges who heard a case taken by Marie Fleming, seeking a [[right to die]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1=Valerie |title=Appalling ordeal of an extraordinary woman |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/appalling-ordeal-of-an-extraordinary-woman-29859091.html |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=Independent.ie |language=en}}</ref> His reference to the [[European Court of Justice]] in 2014 regarding the [[International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles]], resulted in a declaration by the Grand Chamber that the Safe Harbour Decision was invalid.<ref name=\"Aarhus Law\" />\n\nHe subsequently became as a Judge of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal]] upon its establishment in October 2014.<ref name=\"IT Sept 2018\">{{cite news |last1=Leahy |first1=Pat |title=Irish judge takes up key role in European Court of Justice |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/irish-judge-takes-up-key-role-in-european-court-of-justice-1.3627370 |work=The Irish Times |date=12 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocate General ===\nIn May 2018, he was nominated by the [[Government of Ireland]] for appointment as the [[Advocate General]] to the [[European Court of Justice]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/court-of-appeal-judge-nominated-to-european-court-of-justice-1.3507592 | work=Irish Times| title=Court of Appeal judge nominated to European Court of Justice | date=25 May 2018}}</ref> His term began in October 2018 and will expire in October 2024.<ref name=\"Tipperary Live 2018\" /> \n\nIn one of his first opinions, on a reference from the French [[Conseil d'\u00c9tat (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]], he found that Regulation (EU) No 1169/2011 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 25 October 2011 requires that products originating from [[Israeli-occupied territories]] should indicate if these products come from such a territory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adviser to EU court says settlement goods should be labeled |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/adviser-to-eu-court-says-settlement-goods-should-be-labeled/ |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=www.timesofisrael.com}}</ref> His opinion was followed by the Court of Justice.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crisp |first1=James |title=EU's top court rules food from Israeli settlements must carry special label |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/12/eus-top-court-rules-food-israeli-settlements-must-carry-special/ |accessdate=9 December 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hogan, Gerard}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Advocates General of the European Court of Justice]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Court of Appeal (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:High Court judges (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish judges]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "name_user": "ZL10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJudicial career:headings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerard_Hogan"}
{"title_page": "Mark Tremonti", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Mark Tremonti \n| image               = Mark Tremonti (cropped).jpg\n| caption             = Tremonti playing with Alter Bridge at the [[Rock im Park 2014|2014 Rock im Park]]\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Mark Thomas Tremonti\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1974|4|18}}\n| birth_place         = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| origin              = [[Orlando]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| instrument          = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| genre               = <!--Genres in alphabetical order. Please do not change/remove without discussion.-->{{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n* [[speed metal]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n}}\n| occupation          = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active        = 1987\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Wind-up Records|Wind-up]]\n* [[Republic Records|Universal Republic]]\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n* [[EMI]]\n* FRET12\n}}\n| associated_acts     = <!--Please do not add artists Tremonti had collaborated with, i.e. Sevendust, Fozzy, etc. as they do not constitute as associated acts.-->{{flatlist|\n* [[Alter Bridge]]\n* [[Tremonti (band)|Tremonti]]\n* [[Creed (band)|Creed]]}}\n| website             = {{URL|marktremonti.com}}\n}}\n'''Mark Thomas Tremonti''' (born April 18, 1974) is an American musician, singer, songwriter, record producer and author, best known as the lead guitarist of the rock bands [[Creed (band)|Creed]] and [[Alter Bridge]]. He is a founding member of both bands, and has also collaborated with many other artists over the years. He formed his own band, [[Tremonti (band)|Tremonti]], in 2011, releasing the album ''[[All I Was]]'' in July 2012, followed by ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]'' in June 2015, ''[[Dust (Tremonti album)|Dust]]'' in April 2016 and ''A Dying Machine'' in June 2018. The metal rock opera ''A Dying Machine'' has been adapted by Tremonti and science-fiction novelist [[John Shirley]].\n\nSince his early years with Creed, Tremonti has received positive recognition as a guitarist and songwriter and has received a number of accolades, including one [[Grammy Award]] for Creed's single \"[[With Arms Wide Open]].\"<ref name=\"grammy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/g/news_feature_grammy01/grammy01frame.html |title=MTV News: 2001 Grammy Winners |publisher=MTV |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106162455/http://www.mtv.com/bands/g/news_feature_grammy01/grammy01frame.html |archivedate=2012-11-06 }}</ref> He was also named \"Guitarist of the Year\" for three consecutive years by ''[[Guitar World]]'',<ref name=\"prs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.prsguitars.com/artists/profiles/marktremonti/index.html |title=Paul Reed Smith \u2013 Mark Tremonti of Alter Bridge |publisher=[[PRS Guitars]]}}</ref> and in 2011 he was listed in ''[[Total Guitar]]'' magazine as the fourth greatest [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] guitarist of all time.<ref name=\"totalguitar\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rockaaa.com/news/top-twenty-metal-guitarists-revealed-3860 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110323070158/http://www.rockaaa.com/news/top-twenty-metal-guitarists-revealed-3860 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 23, 2011 |title=Top Twenty Metal Guitarists Revealed |date=March 21, 2011 |author=Cameron Pirie |publisher=RockAAA.com }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTremonti was born on April 18, 1974, in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]. He grew up in a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] family of [[Italian people|Italian]] descent in [[Grosse Pointe, Michigan|Grosse Pointe]], just outside Detroit, for most of his childhood before moving to [[Wilmette, Illinois]].<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marktremonti.net/markbio.php|title=Mark Tremonti Biodata|publisher=MarkTremonti.net|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> He began to become enthralled with music, and bought his first guitar at the age of eleven. When he was fifteen, his family moved again to [[Orlando, Florida]],<ref name=\"prs\"/> where he enrolled in [[Lake Highland Preparatory School]]. During this time, his mother was diagnosed with [[systemic lupus erythematosus]], which left Tremonti devastated.<ref name=\"biography\"/>\n\nAfter graduation, he moved to [[Clemson, South Carolina]] to attend [[Clemson University]] to major in finance. After his freshman year in college, he moved back to Florida to enroll in [[Florida State University]], where he was reunited with his then future Creed band mate [[Scott Stapp]], whom Tremonti had known in high school.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1261698/bio|title=Mark Tremonti biography|website=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBefore Creed took off, he worked as a cook at [[Chili\u2019s]].<ref name='youtube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ILq5OPFdyNE|title=Taylor Momsen nos bastidores do That Metal Show|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Creed===\n{{Main|Creed (band)}}\nTremonti is a founding member of the American hard rock band Creed. He formed the band with lead vocalist Scott Stapp in 1994 with fellow members [[Brian Marshall]] and [[Scott Phillips (musician)|Scott Phillips]] joining as bassist and drummer, respectively.<ref name=\"Stapp 2012\">{{cite book |author=Scott Stapp |title=Sinner's Creed |date=2012 |pages=97\u201398 |publisher=Tyndale House |isbn=9781414377216 |quote='What if we just call ourselves Creed?' I asked... At the time it was 1994, my sophomore year.}}</ref> Creed is recognized by many as one of the major acts of the [[post-grunge]] movement of the late 1990s and early 2000s. Tremonti and Stapp have been collectively recognized as one of the most prolific songwriting teams in all of rock music.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/creed_3_/artist.jhtml#biographyEnd|title=Creed \u2013 Full Biography|publisher=MTV|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305004133/http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/creed_3_/artist.jhtml#biographyEnd|archivedate=2011-03-05}}</ref>\n\nThe band released their debut album ''[[My Own Prison]]'' in 1997 to strong mainstream success, selling over six million copies.<ref name=\"creed allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/creed-p278625/biography|title=Creed|website=[[Allmusic]]|author=Steve Huey|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> Four singles were released from the album: \"[[My Own Prison (song)|My Own Prison]]\", \"[[Torn (Creed song)|Torn]]\", \"[[What's This Life For]]\", and \"[[One (Creed song)|One]]\". Each song reached No. 1 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart, making Creed the first band to achieve such a feat with a debut album.<ref name=\"creed allmusic\"/> ''My Own Prison'' was followed in 1999 by ''[[Human Clay]]'', which was an immediate success and certified [[RIAA certification|diamond]] and elevencreed allmusic\"/> The band released four singles from ''Human Clay'': \"[[Higher (Creed song)|Higher]]\", \"[[With Arms Wide Open]]\", \"[[What If (Creed song)|What If]]\", and \"[[Are You Ready? (Creed song)|Are You Ready]]\". \"Higher\" spent a record-breaking 17 weeks on the top of the rock radio charts.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.allbusiness.com/retail-trade/miscellaneous-retail-retail-stores-not/4642080-1.html|title=Creed Goes \"higher' In The Record Books|author=Mark Marone|magazine=Billboard|date=January 21, 2000}}</ref>\n\nMarshall left the band in 2000 due to increasing tension with Stapp and to pursue other interests. He was temporarily replaced by touring bassist [[Brett Hestla]].<ref name=\"scott stapp interview mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/s/stapp_scott/news_feature_080904/index2.jhtml|title=Scott Stapp Breaks His Silence|author=Joe D'Angelo|publisher=MTV|date=August 9, 2004|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040814024301/http://www.mtv.com/bands/s/stapp_scott/news_feature_080904/index2.jhtml|archivedate=August 14, 2004}}</ref>\n\nCreed also won their first, and to date only, [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]] for \"With Arms Wide Open\" in 2001.<ref name=\"grammy\"/> That same year, after a tour, the band released another multi-platinum selling album, ''[[Weathered]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rock.about.com/od/creed/p/creed.htm |title=Creed Biography - Profile of Rock Band Creed|author=Tim Grierson |publisher=[[About.com]]}}</ref> from which six singles were released: \"[[My Sacrifice]]\", \"[[One Last Breath]]\", \"[[Hide (Creed song)|Hide]]\", \"[[Don't Stop Dancing]]\", \"[[Weathered (song)|Weathered]]\", and \"[[Bullets (Creed song)|Bullets]]\". It would be the band's only album without Marshall on bass; Tremonti handled the bass parts himself. The tour to support this record was overwhelmingly successful but ended with a considerably controversial concert in [[Chicago]] that ultimately led to the band's breakup.<ref name=\"suntimes\">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/music/2009/08/creed_they_heard_we_missed_em.html|title=Creed: They heard we missed 'em, now they're back|date=August 25, 2009|author=Jim DeRogatis|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110528224809/http://blogs.suntimes.com/music/2009/08/creed_they_heard_we_missed_em.html|archivedate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe band announced that they had disbanded in 2004, citing tension between Stapp and the other members, Tremonti in particular.<ref name=\"creed break up\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1488149/creed-have-been-split-up-months.jhtml|title=Creed Break Up: Mark Tremonti blames tensions between band, singer Scott Stapp|publisher=MTV |author=Joe D'Angelo |date=June 4, 2004}}</ref> The three instrumental members went on to found [[Alter Bridge]] while Stapp opted for a solo career, and Creed released their ''[[Greatest Hits (Creed album)|Greatest Hits]]'' in November 2004.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nHowever, after months of speculation, despite early claims from Tremonti that Creed would never return,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=51580 |title=ALTER BRIDGE Part Ways With WIND-UP RECORDS |date=April 28, 2006 |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622162236/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=51580 |archivedate=June 22, 2008 }}</ref> it was announced that Creed had reunited with plans for a tour and a new album.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine |author= Jessica Herndon |title=Band Creed Reunites for New Album |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20274934,00.html |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=April 27, 2009}}</ref> The record, ''[[Full Circle (Creed album)|Full Circle]]'', was released in October 2009, accompanied by three singles, \"[[Overcome (Creed song)|Overcome]],\" \"[[Rain (Creed song)|Rain]],\" and \"[[A Thousand Faces]]\". Though a moderate critical success, it ultimately became the band's only album to not be certified by the RIAA. Creed supported the album by touring throughout North and South America, Europe, and Australia during the summers of 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.pollstar.com/blogs/news/archive/2010/04/19/718999.aspx|title=Creed Reveals '20-10' Tour|date=April 19, 2010|author=Jay Smith|magazine=Pollstar|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715102339/http://www.pollstar.com/blogs/news/archive/2010/04/19/718999.aspx|archivedate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe band released a record-breaking [[concert film]] titled ''[[Creed Live]]'' in December 2009.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/article/creed_announce_first_live_dvd|title=Creed Announce First Live DVD |date=November 24, 2009|magazine=Guitar World|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110105612/http://www.guitarworld.com/article/creed_announce_first_live_dvd|archivedate=January 10, 2010}}</ref> Tremonti, Marshall, and Phillips, initially planned to alternate tours between Alter Bridge and Creed with the singers of both bands working on their own projects while the other band is active.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nA fifth Creed album was expected in late 2011 or early 2012 according to Tremonti,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theoaklandpress.com/articles/2010/12/10/entertainment/doc4d01744b28817955477281.txt?viewmode=fullstory|title=Native Detroiter Mark Tremonti embraces space between bands Alter Bridge and Creed|date=December 10, 2010|author=Gary Graff |newspaper=[[The Oakland Press]]}}</ref> and in early 2012 the band reconvened to tour and start work on a fifth album which never began production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2013/11/scott-stapp-proof-of-life-interview|title=Scott Stapp Talks Near-Death Experiences, Michael Jackson & New Creed Album|website=Fuse.tv|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, while promoting his second solo album ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]'', Mark Tremonti claimed in interview with Kerrang that he \"[hasn't] been a close friend of Scott's in 9 years\". He said that Stapp thought that Tremonti, Marshall and Phillips would return to Creed permanently and forget their work with Alter Bridge.  The band felt this was unfair and didn't talk any further about Creed's future during the whole South American Tour in 2012. Alter Bridge kept going at the tour's conclusion.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Alter Bridge===\n{{Main|Alter Bridge}}\n[[File:Mark Tremonti.jpg|thumb|right|210px|Tremonti performing with Alter Bridge in 2007.]]\nAlter Bridge was formed in January 2004 by Tremonti, Marshall, and Phillips after Creed disbanded. They asked [[Myles Kennedy]], formerly of [[The Mayfield Four]] and the future vocalist for [[Slash (musician)|Slash]]'s solo project, to be their singer.<ref name=\"life after creed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/alter_bridge/news_feature_040608|title=Life After Creed: Alter Bridge Look To A Stapp-Free Future|date=June 8, 2004|publisher=[[MTV News]]|author=Joe D'Angelo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629142551/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/alter_bridge/news_feature_040608|archivedate=June 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe newly formed band released their debut album, ''[[One Day Remains]]'', in August 2004 on [[Wind-up Records]]. It saw mostly mixed reviews, but became Alter Bridge's only RIAA-certified album, going gold.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Alter%20Bridge&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50|title=RIAA Searchable database \u2013 Gold and Platinum|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=August 29, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924155118/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Alter%20Bridge&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50|archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref> Three singles were released from ''One Day Remains'': \"[[Open Your Eyes (Alter Bridge song)|Open Your Eyes]]\", \"[[Find the Real]]\", and \"[[Broken Wings (Alter Bridge song)|Broken Wings]]\".\n\nAfter a tour, it was followed by a second album, ''[[Blackbird (Alter Bridge album)|Blackbird]]'', in October 2007 on [[Universal Republic]]. ''Blackbird'' was met with largely positive reviews and released four singles: \"[[Rise Today]],\" \"Ties That Bind,\" \"[[Watch Over You]],\" and \"[[Before Tomorrow Comes]].\" Its [[Blackbird (Alter Bridge song)|title track]] received strong acclaim from reviewers, and its guitar solo, which was performed by both Tremonti and Kennedy, was later named the greatest guitar solo of all time by ''[[Guitarist (magazine)|Guitarist]]'' magazine in 2011.<ref name=\"greatest guitar solo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/guitarist/greatest-guitar-solo-poll-winners-alter-bridge-speak-403308|title=Greatest solo poll: Alter Bridge speak |publisher=[[MusicRadar]]|date=March 21, 2011 |work=[[Guitarist (magazine)|Guitarist]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407061132/http://www.musicradar.com/guitarist/greatest-guitar-solo-poll-winners-alter-bridge-speak-403308|archivedate=April 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAlter Bridge embarked on a successful world tour in support of ''Blackbird'', recording their December 7, 2008, show at the [[Heineken Music Hall]] in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]], for a live DVD titled ''[[Live from Amsterdam (DVD)|Live from Amsterdam]]''.<ref name=\"live dvd\">{{cite web|url=http://roadcrewmag.com/issue/boo-we-got-the-interviews-for-you/article/alter-bridge-to-release-first-ever-live-dvd-live-in-amsterdam|title=ALTER BRIDGE TO RELEASE FIRST-EVER LIVE DVD 'LIVE IN AMSTERDAM'|publisher=Road Crew Mag|accessdate=October 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310072930/http://roadcrewmag.com/issue/boo-we-got-the-interviews-for-you/article/alter-bridge-to-release-first-ever-live-dvd-live-in-amsterdam|archive-date=March 10, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA single-disc version of this DVD was sold exclusively at venues during the [[Creed (band)#Reunion and Full Circle: 2009\u20132010|Creed reunion tour]] in 2009 and on [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] with a [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] version and a deluxe DVD edition scheduled to be released later in stores. However, the distribution in stores was delayed as a result of record label issues multiple times, causing frustration amongst Alter Bridge fans and band members. It was finally released in stores in North America on January 11, 2011, after two years of delays.<ref name=\"live from amsterdam release\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/01/10/alter-bridge-live-from-amsterdam-out-now-usacanada|title=Alter Bridge - Live From Amsterdam - OUT NOW USA/Canada |author=Alter Bridge|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114211620/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/01/10/alter-bridge-live-from-amsterdam-out-now-usacanada|archivedate=2011-01-14}}</ref>\n\nAlter Bridge's third album, ''[[AB III]]'', was released on October 11, 2010, in Europe and the UK on [[Roadrunner Records]],<ref name=\"roadrunner\">{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.co.uk/page/News?news_id=99701 |title=ROADRUNNER WELCOMES ALTER BRIDGE |date=August 31, 2010 |author=Roadrunner Records}}</ref> and on November 9, 2010, in North America on Alter Bridge Recordings via [[EMI]].<ref name=\"alter bridge recordings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2010/10/06/ab-iii-to-hit-stores-in-usa-november-9th-featuring-hit-single-%E2%80%9Cisolation%E2%80%9D|title=AB III to Hit Stores in USA November 9th Featuring Hit Single \"Isolation\"|date=October 6, 2010|work=Alter Bridge's blog|accessdate=October 6, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101014095646/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2010/10/06/ab-iii-to-hit-stores-in-usa-november-9th-featuring-hit-single-%E2%80%9Cisolation%E2%80%9D/ |archivedate=October 14, 2010 }}</ref> A loose [[concept album]],<ref name=\"ab iii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2010/09/08/new-alter-bridge-ab-iii-bio|title=New Alter Bridge - AB III|work=Alter Bridge blogsite|author=Alter Bridge|date=September 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100911025356/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2010/09/08/new-alter-bridge-ab-iii-bio|archivedate=September 11, 2010}}</ref> ''AB III'' has received critical acclaim, with Rick Florino from [[Artistdirect]] calling it a \"sprawling masterpiece.\"<ref name=\"artistdirect ab iii review\">{{cite web|url = http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/alter-bridge-ab-iii-review-5-out-of-5-stars-review/7680895|title=Alter Bridge \"AB III\" Review \u2014 5 out of 5 Stars Review|last=Florino|first=Rick|date=2010-10-12|accessdate=2010-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIts lead single, \"[[Isolation (Alter Bridge song)|Isolation]]\", reached No. 1 on active rock radio and the [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]], the band's first single to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/01/18/alter-bridge-press-release-isolation-goes-1-on-rock-radio|title=Alter Bridge Press Release - Isolation Goes #1 on Rock Radio|date=December 18, 2011|author=[[Alter Bridge]]|publisher=Alter Bridge|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122050804/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/01/18/alter-bridge-press-release-isolation-goes-1-on-rock-radio|archivedate=January 22, 2011}}</ref> The band toured extensively in support of the record, with [[Black Stone Cherry]] and [[Like a Storm]] in the spring of 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/02/03/new-usa-spring-tour-date-like-a-storm-added-to-bill|title=New USA Spring Tour Date + Like A Storm Added to Bill|author=Alter Bridge|publisher=Alter Bridge|date=February 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206082437/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/02/03/new-usa-spring-tour-date-like-a-storm-added-to-bill |archivedate=February 6, 2011}}</ref> in addition to co-headlining the second annual Carnival of Madness Tour with [[Theory of a Deadman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/carnival-of-madness/the-second-annual-car%20nival-of-madness-press-release/224460604247066|title=THE SECOND ANNUAL \"CARNIVAL OF MADNESS\" PRESS RELEASE|date=May 23, 2011|publisher=Facebook}}</ref> The tour continued into January 2012. Four more singles from ''AB III'' have since been released: \"I Know It Hurts\", \"[[Ghost of Days Gone By]]\", \"Wonderful Life\", and \"Life Must Go On\". The band also released a second concert film titled ''[[Live at Wembley (Alter Bridge DVD)|Live at Wembley]]'' on March 26, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fret12.tumblr.com/post/15302733110/between-the-frets-01-04-12|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120714215330/http://fret12.tumblr.com/post/15302733110/between-the-frets-01-04-12|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 14, 2012|title=Alter Bridge Wembley DVD Release Dates Announced|date=January 4, 2012|publisher=Fret 12}}</ref>\n\nThe band reunited in late 2012 and recorded from April to July 2013 their fourth album, ''[[Fortress (Alter Bridge album)|Fortress]]'', released on September 30, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/|title=Alter Bridge|website=Alter Bridge|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> The band reconvened in January 2016 to record their fifth studio album ''[[The Last Hero (album)|The Last Hero]]'', which was released on 7 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/alter-bridge-to-release-the-last-hero-album-in-october/ |title=Alter Bridge To Release 'The Last Hero' Album In October |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=2013-04-17 |accessdate=2016-07-09}}</ref>\n\n===Tremonti===\n{{main|Tremonti (band)}}\n{{sidebar|navbar=off\n| above = Band members\n| contentstyle = text-align:left;\n| content1 = \n;Current members<ref name=\"solo band\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=172450|title=ALTER BRIDGE Guitarist MARK TREMONTI Unveils Solo Band (Video)|date=April 10, 2012|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|work=Blabbermouth.net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414235031/http://legacy.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=172450|archivedate=April 14, 2012}}</ref>\n*Mark Tremonti \u2013 lead vocals, lead and rhythm guitar <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Eric Friedman]] \u2013 rhythm and lead guitar, backing vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n*Garrett Whitlock \u2013 drums <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Wolfgang Van Halen]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n\n;Touring members\n*[[Brian Marshall]] \u2013 bass guitar <small>(2012)</small>\n*Tanner Keegan \u2013 bass guitar <small>(2015\u2013present)</small>}}\n\nDuring the time that Creed was at the end of its career in the early 2000s, Tremonti had intentions to form a [[speed metal]] side project called Downshifter (with [[Hatebreed]] vocalist [[Jamey Jasta]] and [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] drummer [[Joey Jordison]]), but the project never got off the ground.<ref name=\"creed break up\"/> Later, in 2008, Tremonti and his brother formed FRET12, an online musicians' community, [[production company]], and [[record label]], to release his 2008 instructional guitar documentary DVD titled ''Mark Tremonti: The Sound & the Story'',<ref name=\"artwork\">{{cite web|url=http://audioinkradio.com/2012/03/alter-bridge-creed-mark-tremonti-artwork-solo-album|title=Alter Bridge and Creed's Mark Tremonti Reveals Artwork for Solo Album|date=March 20, 2012|publisher=Audio Ink Radio|author=Anne Erickson}}</ref> wherein he teaches all of his guitar solos from Alter Bridge's sophomore release, ''Blackbird''. He also teaches warm-ups, [[guitar tunings#Alternative tunings|alternate tunings]], [[fingerstyle guitar|finger picking]] style, [[legato]] techniques, and other advanced exercises.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nHis DVD, which is the first in ''The Sound & the Story'' series of instructional DVDs, also features guest appearances from [[Myles Kennedy]], [[Michael Angelo Batio]], [[Rusty Cooley]], [[Bill Peck]], and [[Troy Stetina]]. The aforementioned series also includes DVDs by [[Leslie West]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarnoize.com/leslie-west-the-sound-and-the-story-guitar-instruction-documentary-dvd|title=Leslie West The Sound and The Story \u2013 Guitar Instruction/Documentary DVD|publisher=Guitar Noize |date=November 30, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308182922/http://www.guitarnoize.com/leslie-west-the-sound-and-the-story-guitar-instruction-documentary-dvd|archivedate=March 8, 2012}}</ref> and Troy Stetina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/fret12_releases_the_sound_and_the_story_with_troy_stetina.html?no_takeover|title=Fret12 Releases The Sound And The Story With Troy Stetina|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar]]|date=April 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nTremonti later began expressing interest in releasing a [[solo album]] in 2010. \"The bands are so different,\" he said of his two current main projects. \"And I write so much. I'm going to do a solo record because there are some songs that I'd hate to think wouldn't see the light of day because they don't work for Creed or Alter Bridge.\"<ref name=\"solo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/entertainmentnews/Alter-Bridge/article-2754136-detail/article.html|title=Interview: Alter Bridge guitarist Mark Tremonti prepares for Rock City|newspaper=[[Nottingham Post]]|date=October 15, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020183505/http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/entertainmentnews/Alter-Bridge/article-2754136-detail/article.html|archivedate=October 20, 2010}}</ref> He plays guitar and singing lead on all of the songs himself, and former [[Submersed]] members [[Eric Friedman]] and Garrett Whitlock perform on the record as well. Tremonti described the music as \"melody driven\",<ref name=\"solo2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/interviews/alter_bridge_we_wanted_to_stay_relevant_and_not_rely_on_legacy.html|title=Mark Tremonti of Creed and Alter Bridge Interview|author=Steven Rosen|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar Archive]]|date=November 5, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012013945/http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/interviews/alter_bridge_we_wanted_to_stay_relevant_and_not_rely_on_legacy.html|archivedate=October 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a May 2011 interview, Tremonti said that it would be a \"heavier-sounding\" [[thrash metal]] album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/mark_tremonti_working_on_speedthrash_metal_album.html|title=Mark Tremonti Working On Speed/Thrash Metal Album|date=May 18, 2011|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar Archive]]}}</ref> He later said that the album is \"probably heavier than either Creed or Alter Bridge,\" and that it would have \"lots of [[guitar solo|soloing]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/mark-tremonti-talks-solo-album-playing-wembley-arena-with-alter-bridge-creed-and-more/9833329 |title=Mark Tremonti Talks Solo Album, Playing Wembley Arena with Alter Bridge, Creed and More|publisher=[[Artistdirect]]|author=Rick Florino|date=January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn January 20, 2012, Tremonti launched a website for his solo album where fans can sign up to receive news, previews, live streams, and giveaways. A list of working song titles was also included on the webpage, as well as the album title, ''[[All I Was]]''. He later launched a new website for his solo work after the album's release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.licklibrary.com/news/2012/7/3989-mark_tremonti_launches_new_website_and_34all_i_was34_debut_solo_album|title=Mark Tremonti launches new website and \"All I Was\" debut solo album|publisher=Lick Library|date=July 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was set for a July 10, 2012, release on FRET12 Records and \"[[You Waste Your Time]]\" will be the first single from the album,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/490379/creeds-mark-tremonti-releasing-solo-debut|title=Creed's Mark Tremonti Releasing Solo Debut|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=April 26, 2012}}</ref> and according to ''[[FMQB]]'', \"You Waste Your Time\" would be released to [[active rock]] radio stations in May 2012.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fmqb.com/article.asp?id=2444158|title=Quick Hits: Maroon 5, Mark Tremonti, Norah Jones, TLC, Demi Lovato, The Killers, Passion Pit, Van Halen|magazine=[[FMQB]]|date=April 26, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503050953/http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=2444158|archivedate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe entire song was made available for listening on May 6, 2012, one day before its release, on [[Loudwire.com]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/tremonti-you-waste-your-time-song-review|title=Tremonti, 'You Waste Your Time' \u2013 Song Review|publisher=loudwire.com|date=May 6, 2012|author=Mary Ouellette}}</ref> One day after its release, the song reached number 10 on the [[iTunes Store|iTunes Rock Songs Chart]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/mark-tremonti-itunes-top-10-single-you-waste-your-time|title=Mark Tremonti Cracks iTunes Top 10 With Single 'You Waste Your Time'|author=Chad Childers|date=May 8, 2012|publisher=[[Loudwire.com]]}}</ref> and Tremonti's live music video for it premiered on May 17, 2012, on [[Noisecreep]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noisecreep.com/2012/05/17/tremonti-you-waste-your-time-performance-video|title=Tremonti, 'You Waste Your Time': Creed, Alter Bridge Guitarist Makes Solo Debut (VIDEO PREMIERE)|website=[[Noisecreep]]|author=Carlos Ramirez|date=May 17, 2012}}</ref> The album's official release date was announced on [[Ultimate Guitar Archive]] as July 17, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/mark_tremonti_to_unleash_all_i_was_on_july_17.html|title=Mark Tremonti To Unleash 'All I Was' On July 17|date=June 20, 2012|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar Archive]]}}</ref>\n\nHis solo band originally consisted of Friedman and Whitlock alongside Alter Bridge and Creed bassist [[Brian Marshall]] playing bass guitar as a touring member.<ref name=\"solo band\"/> The band performed its first solo concert at The Social in Orlando, Florida, on July 17, 2012, with the performance filmed for a future video release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/tremonti-perform-first-ever-show-july|title=Tremonti To Perform First-Ever Show In July|author=Chad Childers|publisher=Loudwire.com|date=June 9, 2012}}</ref> [[Wolfgang Van Halen]] replaced Brian Marshall as a touring bassist in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MarkTremonti/status/245572382390108160|title=Twitter/MarkTremonti|author=Mark Tremonti|date=September 11, 2012|publisher=[[Twitter]]}}</ref>\n\nTremonti recorded their second album with Wolfgang Van Halen playing bass for the 2015 release. On March 3, 2015, Tremonti released a sample of the song \"Radical Change\" whilst revealing the album title ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]'' and the track listing for the upcoming sophomore effort. On March 17, 2015, Tremonti released another song preview for the track \"Flying Monkeys\" and also gave a concrete release date of June 9, 2015 for ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]''. On March 20, 2015, Tremonti unveiled via Twitter that the first single, titled \"[[Another Heart]]\", was released March 24, 2015.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nOn March 23, 2015, the single ''Another Heart'' was made available for streaming via fret12. On March 27, 2015, the artwork for ''Cauterize'' was revealed and it was revealed that ''Cauterize'' was the first of two albums to be released as the two albums were recorded together. \"The second album titled ''Dust'' will be released in early 2016, \"after [they] record the Alter Bridge record and [they] have that three or four month gap, [he]'ll be looking to tour on it to support it.\" Tremonti said he \"wanted to make sure both albums flowed dynamically. If there were two slow moody songs, [he]'d put one on each album, same thing if there were two really heavy aggressive songs, [he] would split them up evenly. There's isn't a specific theme to one or the other. Each record is mixed\"{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} and that \"it's definitely not the 'b-sides' of this album.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/mark-tremonti-says-forthcoming-dust-album-is-definitely-not-the-b-sides-of-cauterize/|title=MARK TREMONTI Says Forthcoming 'Dust' Album Is 'Definitely Not The B-Sides' Of 'Cauterize'|date=12 May 2015|website=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> ''[[Dust (Tremonti album)|Dust]]'' was released on April 29, 2016 via FRET12 records. The record is produced by [[Michael Baskette|Michael \"Elvis\" Baskette]] who produced Tremonti's past two records and has also produced most of [[Alter Bridge]]'s records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/tremonti-dust-album-artwork-unveiled|title=TREMONTI To Release 'Dust' Album In April|date=19 February 2016|website=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> Tremonti in February announced the band's new album ''A Dying Machine'' to be released later in 2018. The record will be released through [[Napalm Records]] and is again produced by [[Michael Baskette]]. Listening party and performance event for ''A Dying Machine'' are scheduled for May 12. Tremonti will support Iron Maiden on their European tour in June 2018.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/tremonti_releasing_new_album_a_dying_machine_later_this_year.html |title=Tremonti Releasing New Album 'A Dying Machine' Later This Year &#124; Music News @ |website=Ultimate-guitar.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n===Other works===\nTremonti has worked with several artists since his beginning years with Creed. In 2001 he collaborated with comedian [[Larry the Cable Guy]] on his comedy album ''[[Lord, I Apologize]]'', on which Tremonti is credited as a performer and songwriter.<ref>[{{Allmusic |class=album |id=r559255 |tab=credits |pure_url = yes}} allmusic ((( Lord, I Apologize > Credits )))] [[Allmusic]].</ref> Tremonti later recalled, \"We had become friends a long time ago, before his career really started to take off. We joked about getting together and doing a song, and he called me up one day to say he actually wanted to do it. So he sang me his idea, and I went to record my guitar lines that day, and the record went gold.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mike-ragogna/a-conversation-with-creed_b_680948.html |title=A Conversation With Creed's Mark Tremonti |first=Mike |last=Ragogna |date=August 13, 2010 |work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nTremonti later began performing in the [[neo-classical metal]] genre with guitarist [[Michael Angelo Batio]], whose 2004 album ''[[Hands Without Shadows]]'' featured Tremonti as a guest musician on the [[Deep Purple]] cover \"[[Burn (Deep Purple song)|Burn]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marktremonti.net/newsitem.php?id=3|title=Mark Tremonti guests on Michael Angelo Batio album|date=May 24, 2004|publisher=MarkTremonti.net}}</ref> He said that he is \"really good friends\" with Batio, and that working with him was \"an honor.\"<ref name=guitarmessenger>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarmessenger.com/interviews/mark-tremonti-interview-alter-bridge-creed|title=Mark Tremonti Interview (Alter Bridge, Creed)|first=Ivan|last=Chopik|date=November 9, 2007|publisher=Guitar Messenger}}</ref> Batio later appeared on Tremonti's guitar instructional DVD ''The Sound & the Story'' as a guest tutor. In 2009 he appeared on Batio's next album, ''[[Hands Without Shadows 2 \u2013 Voices]]'', performing a solo on the [[Metallica]] medley \"Metallica Rules.\"<ref>[{{Allmusic |class=album |id=r1684609 |tab=credits |pure_url=yes}} allmusic ((( Hands Without Shadows, Vol. 2: Voices > Credits )))]</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Tremonti co-[[record producer|produced]], with Don Gilmore and Kirk Kelsey, some songs on ''[[In Due Time]]'' by [[Submersed]], whom Tremonti helped get signed to [[Wind-up Records]]. Former Submersed guitarist [[Eric Friedman]] recalled his experiences with Tremonti in the studio, saying that watching him \"taught us a lot as far as music and songwriting and being able to get across the things we want to get across.\"<ref name=\"submersed\">{{cite web|url=http://community.musiciansfriend.com/docs/DOC-2699|title=Interview with Submersed: Timing is Everything|first=Bryan|last=Holley|date=August 3, 2010|work=Artist Spotlight|publisher=[[Guitar Center|Musician's Friend]]}}</ref>\n\nTremonti said that producing is not \"something I'd do any time soon again.\"<ref name=guitarmessenger/> He later continued working with other artists on the musical side, in 2005 with [[Fozzy]] on their album ''[[All That Remains (album)|All That Remains]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=21910|title=FOZZY: Ex-MEGADETH Guitarist FRIEDMAN, CREED's TREMONTI To Guest On New CD |date=April 29, 2004|work=Blabbermouth.net|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070319022124/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=21910 |archivedate=March 19, 2007}}</ref> performing a guitar solo on the song \"The Way I Am\". His Alter Bridge band mate Myles Kennedy also appeared on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=29427|title=FOZZY: 'All That Remains' Track Listing, Artwork Revealed|date=November 20, 2004|work=Blabbermouth.net|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060421031113/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=29427|archivedate=April 21, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Tremonti made two guest appearances, one with the [[metalcore]] band [[Bury Your Dead]] on their [[Bury Your Dead (album)|self-titled album]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marktremonti.net/interview.php?id=mtnetmark|title=MarkTremonti.net interview with Mark Tremonti at the Croc Rock in Allentown, PA|date=July 25, 2008|publisher=MarkTremonti.net}}</ref> and another with [[Sevendust]] on the song \"Hope\" from ''[[Chapter VII: Hope & Sorrow]]'', which also featured appearances from Myles Kennedy and [[Chris Daughtry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=90338|title=SEVENDUST: New Song Posted Online|date=February 8, 2008|work=Blabbermouth.net|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410211739/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=90338 |archivedate=April 10, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.melodic.net/?page=news&id=9779|title=New Sevendust Album To Feature Chris Daughtry, Mark Tremonti & Myles Kennedy|date=February 22, 2008|publisher=Melodic.net}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlthough Tremonti does not believe in organized religion or what is in the Bible, he does believe in his own version of God. On December 14, 2002, Tremonti married Victoria Rodriguez, with whom he has two sons, Austen and Pearson. They currently reside in Windermere, Florida.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nTremonti is a collector of [[guitar]]s, [[guitar amplifier|amplifiers]], and [[pinball]] machines, and is known to enjoy playing [[table tennis]].<ref name=\"imdb\"/> He is also an avid fan of reading: \"Five or six years ago,\" he told [[Artistdirect]], \"I started going crazy reading books. Now, I can't get enough.\" He has listed works such as the ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire|Song of Ice and Fire]]'' series by [[George R. R. Martin]], ''[[The Book of the New Sun]]'' by [[Gene Wolfe]], ''[[Old Man's War]]'' by [[John Scalzi]], ''[[The First Law]]'' trilogy by [[Joe Abercrombie]], ''[[The Prophet (book)|The Prophet]]'' by [[Khalil Gibran|Kahlil Gibran]], and ''[[On Writing: A Memoir of the Craft|On Writing]]'' by [[Stephen King]] as some of his favorites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/reading-list-mark-tremonti-of-alter-bridge-and-creed/9867380 |title=Reading List: Mark Tremonti of Alter Bridge and Creed |author=Rick Florino |publisher=[[Artistdirect]] |date=January 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOne of Tremonti's brothers, Michael, is Alter Bridge's fan liaison and publicist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espyrock.com/news/michael-tremonti-comments-on-recent-alter-bridge-rumours |title=Michael Tremonti comments on recent Alter Bridge rumors |publisher=EspyRock |date=July 20, 2010}}</ref> Another brother, Dan, has created the artwork for all of the albums by both Alter Bridge and Creed and is the president and creative director of a design/marketing company called Core Twelve.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.core12.com/ |title=CORE 12: A CREATIVE AGENCY|website=Core12.com|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> Tremonti's mother died in January 2002 and Alter Bridge's song \"In Loving Memory\" is a tribute to her.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/alter_bridge/artist.jhtml#biographyEnd |title=Alter Bridge - Full Biography |publisher=MTV|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and accolades==\n===RIAA certifications===\nThese statistics were compiled from the [[RIAA certification]] online database.<ref name=\"RIAA.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |title=Gold and Platinum database |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archivedate=2007-06-26 }}</ref>\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[My Own Prison]]'': 6\u00d7 platinum (August 2002)\n* ''[[Human Clay]]'': 11\u00d7 platinum, 1\u00d7(+) diamond (January 2004)\n* ''[[Weathered]]'': 6\u00d7 platinum (January 2003)\n* ''[[One Day Remains]]'': gold (November 2004)\n<!--Please do not include ''Full Circle'' on this list without a reliable source. The album is not in the RIAA database, so please do not include it until it has been officially confirmed.-->\n;Compilations\n* ''[[Greatest Hits (Creed album)|Greatest Hits]]'': 2\u00d7 platinum (November 2008)\n\n===Grammy Awards and nominations===\nThe [[Grammy Award]]s are awarded annually by the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]. With Creed, Mark Tremonti has been nominated for three Grammy Awards resulting in one win.<ref name=\"metrolyrics\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/creed-awards-featured.html |title=Awards for Creed |publisher=[[MetroLyrics]]|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n* \"[[With Arms Wide Open]]\" \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]], 2001 (nomination)<ref name=\"grammy\"/>\n* \"With Arms Wide Open\" \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]], 2001 '''(winner)'''<ref name=\"grammy\"/>\n* \"[[My Sacrifice]]\" \u2013 Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal, 2003 (nomination)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/grammy/rockgroup.htm |title=GRAMMY AWARDS:BEST ROCK VOCAL PERFORMANCE BY A DUO OR GROUP |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other accolades===\n'''Loudwire Music Awards'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2013 || Mark Tremonti || Best Guitarist || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2015 || Mark Tremonti || Best Guitarist || {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n'''Metal Hammer Golden Gods Awards'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2008 || Mark Tremonti || Best Shredder || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2014 || Mark Tremonti || Riff Lord || {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\nTremonti was also named \"Guitarist of the Year\" for three consecutive years by ''[[Guitar World]]'' magazine,<ref name=\"prs\"/> and in 2011 he was listed as the fourth greatest [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] guitarist of all time by ''[[Total Guitar]]''.<ref name=\"totalguitar\"/> In addition, and also in 2011, the guitar solo in the [[Alter Bridge]] song \"[[Blackbird (Alter Bridge song)|Blackbird]],\" which Tremonti performed with [[Myles Kennedy]], was named the greatest guitar solo of all time by ''[[Guitarist (magazine)|Guitarist]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"greatest guitar solo\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n===Creed===\n{{Main|Creed discography}}\n;Studio albums\n*''[[My Own Prison]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Human Clay]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Weathered]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Full Circle (Creed album)|Full Circle]]'' (2009)\n;Compilation albums\n*''[[Greatest Hits (Creed album)|Greatest Hits]]'' (2004)\n*''[[With Arms Wide Open: A Retrospective]]'' (2015)\n\n===Alter Bridge===\n{{Main|Alter Bridge discography}}\n;Studio albums\n*''[[One Day Remains]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Blackbird (Alter Bridge album)|Blackbird]]'' (2007)\n*''[[AB III]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Fortress (Alter Bridge album)|Fortress]]'' (2013)\n*''[[The Last Hero (album)|The Last Hero]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Walk the Sky]] (2019)\n\n===Tremonti===\n{{Main|Mark Tremonti discography}}\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[All I Was]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Dust (Tremonti album)|Dust]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[A Dying Machine]]'' (2018)\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''Mark Tremonti: The Sound & the Story'' (2008)\n*''Alter Bridge: Fortress: The Sound & the Story'' (2014)\n*''OSW Review: Episode 84 - Survivor Series'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mark Tremonti}}\n* {{official website|http://www.marktremonti.com}}\n\n{{Tremonti}}\n{{Creed}}\n{{Alter Bridge}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tremonti, Mark}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Alter Bridge members]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Creed (band) members]]\n[[Category:Florida State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Roadrunner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Tremonti (band) members]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Mark Tremonti \n| image               = Mark Tremonti (cropped).jpg\n| caption             = Tremonti playing with Alter Bridge at the [[Rock im Park 2014|2014 Rock im Park]]\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Mark Thomas Tremonti\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1974|4|18}}\n| birth_place         = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| origin              = [[Orlando]], [[Florida]], U.S.\n| instrument          = {{flatlist|\n* Guitar\n* vocals}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| genre               = <!--Genres in alphabetical order. Please do not change/remove without discussion.-->{{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n* [[speed metal]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n}}\n| occupation          = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active        = 1987\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Wind-up Records|Wind-up]]\n* [[Republic Records|Universal Republic]]\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n* [[EMI]]\n* FRET12\n}}\n| associated_acts     = <!--Please do not add artists Tremonti had collaborated with, i.e. Sevendust, Fozzy, etc. as they do not constitute as associated acts.-->{{flatlist|\n* [[Alter Bridge]]\n* [[Tremonti (band)|Tremonti]]\n* [[Creed (band)|Creed]]}}\n| website             = {{URL|marktremonti.com}}\n}}\n'''Mark Thomas Tremonti''' (born April 18, 1974) is an American musician, singer, songwriter, record producer and author, best known as the lead guitarist of the rock bands [[Creed (band)|Creed]] and [[Alter Bridge]]. He is a founding member of both bands, and has also collaborated with many other artists over the years. He formed his own band, [[Tremonti (band)|Tremonti]], in 2011, releasing the album ''[[All I Was]]'' in July 2012, followed by ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]'' in June 2015, ''[[Dust (Tremonti album)|Dust]]'' in April 2016 and ''A Dying Machine'' in June 2018. The metal rock opera ''A Dying Machine'' has been adapted by Tremonti and science-fiction novelist [[John Shirley]].\n\nSince his early years with Creed, Tremonti has received positive recognition as a guitarist and songwriter and has received a number of accolades, including one [[Grammy Award]] for Creed's single \"[[With Arms Wide Open]].\"<ref name=\"grammy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/g/news_feature_grammy01/grammy01frame.html |title=MTV News: 2001 Grammy Winners |publisher=MTV |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106162455/http://www.mtv.com/bands/g/news_feature_grammy01/grammy01frame.html |archivedate=2012-11-06 }}</ref> He was also named \"Guitarist of the Year\" for three consecutive years by ''[[Guitar World]]'',<ref name=\"prs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.prsguitars.com/artists/profiles/marktremonti/index.html |title=Paul Reed Smith \u2013 Mark Tremonti of Alter Bridge |publisher=[[PRS Guitars]]}}</ref> and in 2011 he was listed in ''[[Total Guitar]]'' magazine as the fourth greatest [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] guitarist of all time.<ref name=\"totalguitar\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rockaaa.com/news/top-twenty-metal-guitarists-revealed-3860 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110323070158/http://www.rockaaa.com/news/top-twenty-metal-guitarists-revealed-3860 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 23, 2011 |title=Top Twenty Metal Guitarists Revealed |date=March 21, 2011 |author=Cameron Pirie |publisher=RockAAA.com }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nTremonti was born on April 18, 1974, in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]. He grew up in a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] family of [[Italian people|Italian]] descent in [[Grosse Pointe, Michigan|Grosse Pointe]], just outside Detroit, for most of his childhood before moving to [[Wilmette, Illinois]].<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marktremonti.net/markbio.php|title=Mark Tremonti Biodata|publisher=MarkTremonti.net|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> He began to become enthralled with music, and bought his first guitar at the age of eleven. When he was fifteen, his family moved again to [[Orlando, Florida]],<ref name=\"prs\"/> where he enrolled in [[Lake Highland Preparatory School]]. During this time, his mother was diagnosed with [[systemic lupus erythematosus]], which left Tremonti devastated.<ref name=\"biography\"/>\n\nAfter graduation, he moved to [[Clemson, South Carolina]] to attend [[Clemson University]] to major in finance. After his freshman year in college, he moved back to Florida to enroll in [[Florida State University]], where he was reunited with his then future Creed band mate [[Scott Stapp]], whom Tremonti had known in high school.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1261698/bio|title=Mark Tremonti biography|website=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBefore Creed took off, he worked as a cook at [[Chili\u2019s]].<ref name='youtube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ILq5OPFdyNE|title=Taylor Momsen nos bastidores do That Metal Show|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Creed===\n{{Main|Creed (band)}}\nTremonti is a founding member of the American hard rock band Creed. He formed the band with lead vocalist Scott Stapp in 1994 with fellow members [[Brian Marshall]] and [[Scott Phillips (musician)|Scott Phillips]] joining as bassist and drummer, respectively.<ref name=\"Stapp 2012\">{{cite book |author=Scott Stapp |title=Sinner's Creed |date=2012 |pages=97\u201398 |publisher=Tyndale House |isbn=9781414377216 |quote='What if we just call ourselves Creed?' I asked... At the time it was 1994, my sophomore year.}}</ref> Creed is recognized by many as one of the major acts of the [[post-grunge]] movement of the late 1990s and early 2000s. Tremonti and Stapp have been collectively recognized as one of the most prolific songwriting teams in all of rock music.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/creed_3_/artist.jhtml#biographyEnd|title=Creed \u2013 Full Biography|publisher=MTV|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110305004133/http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/creed_3_/artist.jhtml#biographyEnd|archivedate=2011-03-05}}</ref>\n\nThe band released their debut album ''[[My Own Prison]]'' in 1997 to strong mainstream success, selling over six million copies.<ref name=\"creed allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/creed-p278625/biography|title=Creed|website=[[Allmusic]]|author=Steve Huey|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> Four singles were released from the album: \"[[My Own Prison (song)|My Own Prison]]\", \"[[Torn (Creed song)|Torn]]\", \"[[What's This Life For]]\", and \"[[One (Creed song)|One]]\". Each song reached No. 1 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]] chart, making Creed the first band to achieve such a feat with a debut album.<ref name=\"creed allmusic\"/> ''My Own Prison'' was followed in 1999 by ''[[Human Clay]]'', which was an immediate success and certified [[RIAA certification|diamond]] and eleven times platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref name=\"creed allmusic\"/> The band released four singles from ''Human Clay'': \"[[Higher (Creed song)|Higher]]\", \"[[With Arms Wide Open]]\", \"[[What If (Creed song)|What If]]\", and \"[[Are You Ready? (Creed song)|Are You Ready]]\". \"Higher\" spent a record-breaking 17 weeks on the top of the rock radio charts.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.allbusiness.com/retail-trade/miscellaneous-retail-retail-stores-not/4642080-1.html|title=Creed Goes \"higher' In The Record Books|author=Mark Marone|magazine=Billboard|date=January 21, 2000}}</ref>\n\nMarshall left the band in 2000 due to increasing tension with Stapp and to pursue other interests. He was temporarily replaced by touring bassist [[Brett Hestla]].<ref name=\"scott stapp interview mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/s/stapp_scott/news_feature_080904/index2.jhtml|title=Scott Stapp Breaks His Silence|author=Joe D'Angelo|publisher=MTV|date=August 9, 2004|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040814024301/http://www.mtv.com/bands/s/stapp_scott/news_feature_080904/index2.jhtml|archivedate=August 14, 2004}}</ref>\n\nCreed also won their first, and to date only, [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]] for \"With Arms Wide Open\" in 2001.<ref name=\"grammy\"/> That same year, after a tour, the band released another multi-platinum selling album, ''[[Weathered]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rock.about.com/od/creed/p/creed.htm |title=Creed Biography - Profile of Rock Band Creed|author=Tim Grierson |publisher=[[About.com]]}}</ref> from which six singles were released: \"[[My Sacrifice]]\", \"[[One Last Breath]]\", \"[[Hide (Creed song)|Hide]]\", \"[[Don't Stop Dancing]]\", \"[[Weathered (song)|Weathered]]\", and \"[[Bullets (Creed song)|Bullets]]\". It would be the band's only album without Marshall on bass; Tremonti handled the bass parts himself. The tour to support this record was overwhelmingly successful but ended with a considerably controversial concert in [[Chicago]] that ultimately led to the band's breakup.<ref name=\"suntimes\">{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/music/2009/08/creed_they_heard_we_missed_em.html|title=Creed: They heard we missed 'em, now they're back|date=August 25, 2009|author=Jim DeRogatis|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110528224809/http://blogs.suntimes.com/music/2009/08/creed_they_heard_we_missed_em.html|archivedate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe band announced that they had disbanded in 2004, citing tension between Stapp and the other members, Tremonti in particular.<ref name=\"creed break up\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1488149/creed-have-been-split-up-months.jhtml|title=Creed Break Up: Mark Tremonti blames tensions between band, singer Scott Stapp|publisher=MTV |author=Joe D'Angelo |date=June 4, 2004}}</ref> The three instrumental members went on to found [[Alter Bridge]] while Stapp opted for a solo career, and Creed released their ''[[Greatest Hits (Creed album)|Greatest Hits]]'' in November 2004.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nHowever, after months of speculation, despite early claims from Tremonti that Creed would never return,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=51580 |title=ALTER BRIDGE Part Ways With WIND-UP RECORDS |date=April 28, 2006 |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622162236/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=51580 |archivedate=June 22, 2008 }}</ref> it was announced that Creed had reunited with plans for a tour and a new album.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine |author= Jessica Herndon |title=Band Creed Reunites for New Album |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20274934,00.html |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=April 27, 2009}}</ref> The record, ''[[Full Circle (Creed album)|Full Circle]]'', was released in October 2009, accompanied by three singles, \"[[Overcome (Creed song)|Overcome]],\" \"[[Rain (Creed song)|Rain]],\" and \"[[A Thousand Faces]]\". Though a moderate critical success, it ultimately became the band's only album to not be certified by the RIAA. Creed supported the album by touring throughout North and South America, Europe, and Australia during the summers of 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.pollstar.com/blogs/news/archive/2010/04/19/718999.aspx|title=Creed Reveals '20-10' Tour|date=April 19, 2010|author=Jay Smith|magazine=Pollstar|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715102339/http://www.pollstar.com/blogs/news/archive/2010/04/19/718999.aspx|archivedate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe band released a record-breaking [[concert film]] titled ''[[Creed Live]]'' in December 2009.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/article/creed_announce_first_live_dvd|title=Creed Announce First Live DVD |date=November 24, 2009|magazine=Guitar World|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110105612/http://www.guitarworld.com/article/creed_announce_first_live_dvd|archivedate=January 10, 2010}}</ref> Tremonti, Marshall, and Phillips, initially planned to alternate tours between Alter Bridge and Creed with the singers of both bands working on their own projects while the other band is active.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nA fifth Creed album was expected in late 2011 or early 2012 according to Tremonti,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theoaklandpress.com/articles/2010/12/10/entertainment/doc4d01744b28817955477281.txt?viewmode=fullstory|title=Native Detroiter Mark Tremonti embraces space between bands Alter Bridge and Creed|date=December 10, 2010|author=Gary Graff |newspaper=[[The Oakland Press]]}}</ref> and in early 2012 the band reconvened to tour and start work on a fifth album which never began production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2013/11/scott-stapp-proof-of-life-interview|title=Scott Stapp Talks Near-Death Experiences, Michael Jackson & New Creed Album|website=Fuse.tv|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, while promoting his second solo album ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]'', Mark Tremonti claimed in interview with Kerrang that he \"[hasn't] been a close friend of Scott's in 9 years\". He said that Stapp thought that Tremonti, Marshall and Phillips would return to Creed permanently and forget their work with Alter Bridge.  The band felt this was unfair and didn't talk any further about Creed's future during the whole South American Tour in 2012. Alter Bridge kept going at the tour's conclusion.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Alter Bridge===\n{{Main|Alter Bridge}}\n[[File:Mark Tremonti.jpg|thumb|right|210px|Tremonti performing with Alter Bridge in 2007.]]\nAlter Bridge was formed in January 2004 by Tremonti, Marshall, and Phillips after Creed disbanded. They asked [[Myles Kennedy]], formerly of [[The Mayfield Four]] and the future vocalist for [[Slash (musician)|Slash]]'s solo project, to be their singer.<ref name=\"life after creed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/alter_bridge/news_feature_040608|title=Life After Creed: Alter Bridge Look To A Stapp-Free Future|date=June 8, 2004|publisher=[[MTV News]]|author=Joe D'Angelo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629142551/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/alter_bridge/news_feature_040608|archivedate=June 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe newly formed band released their debut album, ''[[One Day Remains]]'', in August 2004 on [[Wind-up Records]]. It saw mostly mixed reviews, but became Alter Bridge's only RIAA-certified album, going gold.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Alter%20Bridge&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50|title=RIAA Searchable database \u2013 Gold and Platinum|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=August 29, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924155118/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Alter%20Bridge&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50|archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref> Three singles were released from ''One Day Remains'': \"[[Open Your Eyes (Alter Bridge song)|Open Your Eyes]]\", \"[[Find the Real]]\", and \"[[Broken Wings (Alter Bridge song)|Broken Wings]]\".\n\nAfter a tour, it was followed by a second album, ''[[Blackbird (Alter Bridge album)|Blackbird]]'', in October 2007 on [[Universal Republic]]. ''Blackbird'' was met with largely positive reviews and released four singles: \"[[Rise Today]],\" \"Ties That Bind,\" \"[[Watch Over You]],\" and \"[[Before Tomorrow Comes]].\" Its [[Blackbird (Alter Bridge song)|title track]] received strong acclaim from reviewers, and its guitar solo, which was performed by both Tremonti and Kennedy, was later named the greatest guitar solo of all time by ''[[Guitarist (magazine)|Guitarist]]'' magazine in 2011.<ref name=\"greatest guitar solo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/guitarist/greatest-guitar-solo-poll-winners-alter-bridge-speak-403308|title=Greatest solo poll: Alter Bridge speak |publisher=[[MusicRadar]]|date=March 21, 2011 |work=[[Guitarist (magazine)|Guitarist]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407061132/http://www.musicradar.com/guitarist/greatest-guitar-solo-poll-winners-alter-bridge-speak-403308|archivedate=April 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAlter Bridge embarked on a successful world tour in support of ''Blackbird'', recording their December 7, 2008, show at the [[Heineken Music Hall]] in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]], for a live DVD titled ''[[Live from Amsterdam (DVD)|Live from Amsterdam]]''.<ref name=\"live dvd\">{{cite web|url=http://roadcrewmag.com/issue/boo-we-got-the-interviews-for-you/article/alter-bridge-to-release-first-ever-live-dvd-live-in-amsterdam|title=ALTER BRIDGE TO RELEASE FIRST-EVER LIVE DVD 'LIVE IN AMSTERDAM'|publisher=Road Crew Mag|accessdate=October 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310072930/http://roadcrewmag.com/issue/boo-we-got-the-interviews-for-you/article/alter-bridge-to-release-first-ever-live-dvd-live-in-amsterdam|archive-date=March 10, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA single-disc version of this DVD was sold exclusively at venues during the [[Creed (band)#Reunion and Full Circle: 2009\u20132010|Creed reunion tour]] in 2009 and on [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] with a [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] version and a deluxe DVD edition scheduled to be released later in stores. However, the distribution in stores was delayed as a result of record label issues multiple times, causing frustration amongst Alter Bridge fans and band members. It was finally released in stores in North America on January 11, 2011, after two years of delays.<ref name=\"live from amsterdam release\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/01/10/alter-bridge-live-from-amsterdam-out-now-usacanada|title=Alter Bridge - Live From Amsterdam - OUT NOW USA/Canada |author=Alter Bridge|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114211620/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/01/10/alter-bridge-live-from-amsterdam-out-now-usacanada|archivedate=2011-01-14}}</ref>\n\nAlter Bridge's third album, ''[[AB III]]'', was released on October 11, 2010, in Europe and the UK on [[Roadrunner Records]],<ref name=\"roadrunner\">{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.co.uk/page/News?news_id=99701 |title=ROADRUNNER WELCOMES ALTER BRIDGE |date=August 31, 2010 |author=Roadrunner Records}}</ref> and on November 9, 2010, in North America on Alter Bridge Recordings via [[EMI]].<ref name=\"alter bridge recordings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2010/10/06/ab-iii-to-hit-stores-in-usa-november-9th-featuring-hit-single-%E2%80%9Cisolation%E2%80%9D|title=AB III to Hit Stores in USA November 9th Featuring Hit Single \"Isolation\"|date=October 6, 2010|work=Alter Bridge's blog|accessdate=October 6, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101014095646/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2010/10/06/ab-iii-to-hit-stores-in-usa-november-9th-featuring-hit-single-%E2%80%9Cisolation%E2%80%9D/ |archivedate=October 14, 2010 }}</ref> A loose [[concept album]],<ref name=\"ab iii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2010/09/08/new-alter-bridge-ab-iii-bio|title=New Alter Bridge - AB III|work=Alter Bridge blogsite|author=Alter Bridge|date=September 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100911025356/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2010/09/08/new-alter-bridge-ab-iii-bio|archivedate=September 11, 2010}}</ref> ''AB III'' has received critical acclaim, with Rick Florino from [[Artistdirect]] calling it a \"sprawling masterpiece.\"<ref name=\"artistdirect ab iii review\">{{cite web|url = http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/alter-bridge-ab-iii-review-5-out-of-5-stars-review/7680895|title=Alter Bridge \"AB III\" Review \u2014 5 out of 5 Stars Review|last=Florino|first=Rick|date=2010-10-12|accessdate=2010-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIts lead single, \"[[Isolation (Alter Bridge song)|Isolation]]\", reached No. 1 on active rock radio and the [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]], the band's first single to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/01/18/alter-bridge-press-release-isolation-goes-1-on-rock-radio|title=Alter Bridge Press Release - Isolation Goes #1 on Rock Radio|date=December 18, 2011|author=[[Alter Bridge]]|publisher=Alter Bridge|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122050804/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/01/18/alter-bridge-press-release-isolation-goes-1-on-rock-radio|archivedate=January 22, 2011}}</ref> The band toured extensively in support of the record, with [[Black Stone Cherry]] and [[Like a Storm]] in the spring of 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/02/03/new-usa-spring-tour-date-like-a-storm-added-to-bill|title=New USA Spring Tour Date + Like A Storm Added to Bill|author=Alter Bridge|publisher=Alter Bridge|date=February 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206082437/http://www.alterbridge.com/html/2011/02/03/new-usa-spring-tour-date-like-a-storm-added-to-bill |archivedate=February 6, 2011}}</ref> in addition to co-headlining the second annual Carnival of Madness Tour with [[Theory of a Deadman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/carnival-of-madness/the-second-annual-car%20nival-of-madness-press-release/224460604247066|title=THE SECOND ANNUAL \"CARNIVAL OF MADNESS\" PRESS RELEASE|date=May 23, 2011|publisher=Facebook}}</ref> The tour continued into January 2012. Four more singles from ''AB III'' have since been released: \"I Know It Hurts\", \"[[Ghost of Days Gone By]]\", \"Wonderful Life\", and \"Life Must Go On\". The band also released a second concert film titled ''[[Live at Wembley (Alter Bridge DVD)|Live at Wembley]]'' on March 26, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fret12.tumblr.com/post/15302733110/between-the-frets-01-04-12|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120714215330/http://fret12.tumblr.com/post/15302733110/between-the-frets-01-04-12|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 14, 2012|title=Alter Bridge Wembley DVD Release Dates Announced|date=January 4, 2012|publisher=Fret 12}}</ref>\n\nThe band reunited in late 2012 and recorded from April to July 2013 their fourth album, ''[[Fortress (Alter Bridge album)|Fortress]]'', released on September 30, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alterbridge.com/|title=Alter Bridge|website=Alter Bridge|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> The band reconvened in January 2016 to record their fifth studio album ''[[The Last Hero (album)|The Last Hero]]'', which was released on 7 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/alter-bridge-to-release-the-last-hero-album-in-october/ |title=Alter Bridge To Release 'The Last Hero' Album In October |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=2013-04-17 |accessdate=2016-07-09}}</ref>\n\n===Tremonti===\n{{main|Tremonti (band)}}\n{{sidebar|navbar=off\n| above = Band members\n| contentstyle = text-align:left;\n| content1 = \n;Current members<ref name=\"solo band\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=172450|title=ALTER BRIDGE Guitarist MARK TREMONTI Unveils Solo Band (Video)|date=April 10, 2012|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|work=Blabbermouth.net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414235031/http://legacy.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=172450|archivedate=April 14, 2012}}</ref>\n*Mark Tremonti \u2013 lead vocals, lead and rhythm guitar <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Eric Friedman]] \u2013 rhythm and lead guitar, backing vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n*Garrett Whitlock \u2013 drums <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Wolfgang Van Halen]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n\n;Touring members\n*[[Brian Marshall]] \u2013 bass guitar <small>(2012)</small>\n*Tanner Keegan \u2013 bass guitar <small>(2015\u2013present)</small>}}\n\nDuring the time that Creed was at the end of its career in the early 2000s, Tremonti had intentions to form a [[speed metal]] side project called Downshifter (with [[Hatebreed]] vocalist [[Jamey Jasta]] and [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] drummer [[Joey Jordison]]), but the project never got off the ground.<ref name=\"creed break up\"/> Later, in 2008, Tremonti and his brother formed FRET12, an online musicians' community, [[production company]], and [[record label]], to release his 2008 instructional guitar documentary DVD titled ''Mark Tremonti: The Sound & the Story'',<ref name=\"artwork\">{{cite web|url=http://audioinkradio.com/2012/03/alter-bridge-creed-mark-tremonti-artwork-solo-album|title=Alter Bridge and Creed's Mark Tremonti Reveals Artwork for Solo Album|date=March 20, 2012|publisher=Audio Ink Radio|author=Anne Erickson}}</ref> wherein he teaches all of his guitar solos from Alter Bridge's sophomore release, ''Blackbird''. He also teaches warm-ups, [[guitar tunings#Alternative tunings|alternate tunings]], [[fingerstyle guitar|finger picking]] style, [[legato]] techniques, and other advanced exercises.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nHis DVD, which is the first in ''The Sound & the Story'' series of instructional DVDs, also features guest appearances from [[Myles Kennedy]], [[Michael Angelo Batio]], [[Rusty Cooley]], [[Bill Peck]], and [[Troy Stetina]]. The aforementioned series also includes DVDs by [[Leslie West]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarnoize.com/leslie-west-the-sound-and-the-story-guitar-instruction-documentary-dvd|title=Leslie West The Sound and The Story \u2013 Guitar Instruction/Documentary DVD|publisher=Guitar Noize |date=November 30, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308182922/http://www.guitarnoize.com/leslie-west-the-sound-and-the-story-guitar-instruction-documentary-dvd|archivedate=March 8, 2012}}</ref> and Troy Stetina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/fret12_releases_the_sound_and_the_story_with_troy_stetina.html?no_takeover|title=Fret12 Releases The Sound And The Story With Troy Stetina|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar]]|date=April 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nTremonti later began expressing interest in releasing a [[solo album]] in 2010. \"The bands are so different,\" he said of his two current main projects. \"And I write so much. I'm going to do a solo record because there are some songs that I'd hate to think wouldn't see the light of day because they don't work for Creed or Alter Bridge.\"<ref name=\"solo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/entertainmentnews/Alter-Bridge/article-2754136-detail/article.html|title=Interview: Alter Bridge guitarist Mark Tremonti prepares for Rock City|newspaper=[[Nottingham Post]]|date=October 15, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020183505/http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/entertainmentnews/Alter-Bridge/article-2754136-detail/article.html|archivedate=October 20, 2010}}</ref> He plays guitar and singing lead on all of the songs himself, and former [[Submersed]] members [[Eric Friedman]] and Garrett Whitlock perform on the record as well. Tremonti described the music as \"melody driven\",<ref name=\"solo2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/interviews/alter_bridge_we_wanted_to_stay_relevant_and_not_rely_on_legacy.html|title=Mark Tremonti of Creed and Alter Bridge Interview|author=Steven Rosen|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar Archive]]|date=November 5, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012013945/http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/interviews/alter_bridge_we_wanted_to_stay_relevant_and_not_rely_on_legacy.html|archivedate=October 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a May 2011 interview, Tremonti said that it would be a \"heavier-sounding\" [[thrash metal]] album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/mark_tremonti_working_on_speedthrash_metal_album.html|title=Mark Tremonti Working On Speed/Thrash Metal Album|date=May 18, 2011|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar Archive]]}}</ref> He later said that the album is \"probably heavier than either Creed or Alter Bridge,\" and that it would have \"lots of [[guitar solo|soloing]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/mark-tremonti-talks-solo-album-playing-wembley-arena-with-alter-bridge-creed-and-more/9833329 |title=Mark Tremonti Talks Solo Album, Playing Wembley Arena with Alter Bridge, Creed and More|publisher=[[Artistdirect]]|author=Rick Florino|date=January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn January 20, 2012, Tremonti launched a website for his solo album where fans can sign up to receive news, previews, live streams, and giveaways. A list of working song titles was also included on the webpage, as well as the album title, ''[[All I Was]]''. He later launched a new website for his solo work after the album's release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.licklibrary.com/news/2012/7/3989-mark_tremonti_launches_new_website_and_34all_i_was34_debut_solo_album|title=Mark Tremonti launches new website and \"All I Was\" debut solo album|publisher=Lick Library|date=July 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt was set for a July 10, 2012, release on FRET12 Records and \"[[You Waste Your Time]]\" will be the first single from the album,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/490379/creeds-mark-tremonti-releasing-solo-debut|title=Creed's Mark Tremonti Releasing Solo Debut|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=April 26, 2012}}</ref> and according to ''[[FMQB]]'', \"You Waste Your Time\" would be released to [[active rock]] radio stations in May 2012.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fmqb.com/article.asp?id=2444158|title=Quick Hits: Maroon 5, Mark Tremonti, Norah Jones, TLC, Demi Lovato, The Killers, Passion Pit, Van Halen|magazine=[[FMQB]]|date=April 26, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503050953/http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=2444158|archivedate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe entire song was made available for listening on May 6, 2012, one day before its release, on [[Loudwire.com]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/tremonti-you-waste-your-time-song-review|title=Tremonti, 'You Waste Your Time' \u2013 Song Review|publisher=loudwire.com|date=May 6, 2012|author=Mary Ouellette}}</ref> One day after its release, the song reached number 10 on the [[iTunes Store|iTunes Rock Songs Chart]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/mark-tremonti-itunes-top-10-single-you-waste-your-time|title=Mark Tremonti Cracks iTunes Top 10 With Single 'You Waste Your Time'|author=Chad Childers|date=May 8, 2012|publisher=[[Loudwire.com]]}}</ref> and Tremonti's live music video for it premiered on May 17, 2012, on [[Noisecreep]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noisecreep.com/2012/05/17/tremonti-you-waste-your-time-performance-video|title=Tremonti, 'You Waste Your Time': Creed, Alter Bridge Guitarist Makes Solo Debut (VIDEO PREMIERE)|website=[[Noisecreep]]|author=Carlos Ramirez|date=May 17, 2012}}</ref> The album's official release date was announced on [[Ultimate Guitar Archive]] as July 17, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/mark_tremonti_to_unleash_all_i_was_on_july_17.html|title=Mark Tremonti To Unleash 'All I Was' On July 17|date=June 20, 2012|publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar Archive]]}}</ref>\n\nHis solo band originally consisted of Friedman and Whitlock alongside Alter Bridge and Creed bassist [[Brian Marshall]] playing bass guitar as a touring member.<ref name=\"solo band\"/> The band performed its first solo concert at The Social in Orlando, Florida, on July 17, 2012, with the performance filmed for a future video release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/tremonti-perform-first-ever-show-july|title=Tremonti To Perform First-Ever Show In July|author=Chad Childers|publisher=Loudwire.com|date=June 9, 2012}}</ref> [[Wolfgang Van Halen]] replaced Brian Marshall as a touring bassist in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MarkTremonti/status/245572382390108160|title=Twitter/MarkTremonti|author=Mark Tremonti|date=September 11, 2012|publisher=[[Twitter]]}}</ref>\n\nTremonti recorded their second album with Wolfgang Van Halen playing bass for the 2015 release. On March 3, 2015, Tremonti released a sample of the song \"Radical Change\" whilst revealing the album title ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]'' and the track listing for the upcoming sophomore effort. On March 17, 2015, Tremonti released another song preview for the track \"Flying Monkeys\" and also gave a concrete release date of June 9, 2015 for ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]''. On March 20, 2015, Tremonti unveiled via Twitter that the first single, titled \"[[Another Heart]]\", was released March 24, 2015.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nOn March 23, 2015, the single ''Another Heart'' was made available for streaming via fret12. On March 27, 2015, the artwork for ''Cauterize'' was revealed and it was revealed that ''Cauterize'' was the first of two albums to be released as the two albums were recorded together. \"The second album titled ''Dust'' will be released in early 2016, \"after [they] record the Alter Bridge record and [they] have that three or four month gap, [he]'ll be looking to tour on it to support it.\" Tremonti said he \"wanted to make sure both albums flowed dynamically. If there were two slow moody songs, [he]'d put one on each album, same thing if there were two really heavy aggressive songs, [he] would split them up evenly. There's isn't a specific theme to one or the other. Each record is mixed\"{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} and that \"it's definitely not the 'b-sides' of this album.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/mark-tremonti-says-forthcoming-dust-album-is-definitely-not-the-b-sides-of-cauterize/|title=MARK TREMONTI Says Forthcoming 'Dust' Album Is 'Definitely Not The B-Sides' Of 'Cauterize'|date=12 May 2015|website=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> ''[[Dust (Tremonti album)|Dust]]'' was released on April 29, 2016 via FRET12 records. The record is produced by [[Michael Baskette|Michael \"Elvis\" Baskette]] who produced Tremonti's past two records and has also produced most of [[Alter Bridge]]'s records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/tremonti-dust-album-artwork-unveiled|title=TREMONTI To Release 'Dust' Album In April|date=19 February 2016|website=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> Tremonti in February announced the band's new album ''A Dying Machine'' to be released later in 2018. The record will be released through [[Napalm Records]] and is again produced by [[Michael Baskette]]. Listening party and performance event for ''A Dying Machine'' are scheduled for May 12. Tremonti will support Iron Maiden on their European tour in June 2018.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/tremonti_releasing_new_album_a_dying_machine_later_this_year.html |title=Tremonti Releasing New Album 'A Dying Machine' Later This Year &#124; Music News @ |website=Ultimate-guitar.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n===Other works===\nTremonti has worked with several artists since his beginning years with Creed. In 2001 he collaborated with comedian [[Larry the Cable Guy]] on his comedy album ''[[Lord, I Apologize]]'', on which Tremonti is credited as a performer and songwriter.<ref>[{{Allmusic |class=album |id=r559255 |tab=credits |pure_url = yes}} allmusic ((( Lord, I Apologize > Credits )))] [[Allmusic]].</ref> Tremonti later recalled, \"We had become friends a long time ago, before his career really started to take off. We joked about getting together and doing a song, and he called me up one day to say he actually wanted to do it. So he sang me his idea, and I went to record my guitar lines that day, and the record went gold.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mike-ragogna/a-conversation-with-creed_b_680948.html |title=A Conversation With Creed's Mark Tremonti |first=Mike |last=Ragogna |date=August 13, 2010 |work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nTremonti later began performing in the [[neo-classical metal]] genre with guitarist [[Michael Angelo Batio]], whose 2004 album ''[[Hands Without Shadows]]'' featured Tremonti as a guest musician on the [[Deep Purple]] cover \"[[Burn (Deep Purple song)|Burn]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marktremonti.net/newsitem.php?id=3|title=Mark Tremonti guests on Michael Angelo Batio album|date=May 24, 2004|publisher=MarkTremonti.net}}</ref> He said that he is \"really good friends\" with Batio, and that working with him was \"an honor.\"<ref name=guitarmessenger>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarmessenger.com/interviews/mark-tremonti-interview-alter-bridge-creed|title=Mark Tremonti Interview (Alter Bridge, Creed)|first=Ivan|last=Chopik|date=November 9, 2007|publisher=Guitar Messenger}}</ref> Batio later appeared on Tremonti's guitar instructional DVD ''The Sound & the Story'' as a guest tutor. In 2009 he appeared on Batio's next album, ''[[Hands Without Shadows 2 \u2013 Voices]]'', performing a solo on the [[Metallica]] medley \"Metallica Rules.\"<ref>[{{Allmusic |class=album |id=r1684609 |tab=credits |pure_url=yes}} allmusic ((( Hands Without Shadows, Vol. 2: Voices > Credits )))]</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Tremonti co-[[record producer|produced]], with Don Gilmore and Kirk Kelsey, some songs on ''[[In Due Time]]'' by [[Submersed]], whom Tremonti helped get signed to [[Wind-up Records]]. Former Submersed guitarist [[Eric Friedman]] recalled his experiences with Tremonti in the studio, saying that watching him \"taught us a lot as far as music and songwriting and being able to get across the things we want to get across.\"<ref name=\"submersed\">{{cite web|url=http://community.musiciansfriend.com/docs/DOC-2699|title=Interview with Submersed: Timing is Everything|first=Bryan|last=Holley|date=August 3, 2010|work=Artist Spotlight|publisher=[[Guitar Center|Musician's Friend]]}}</ref>\n\nTremonti said that producing is not \"something I'd do any time soon again.\"<ref name=guitarmessenger/> He later continued working with other artists on the musical side, in 2005 with [[Fozzy]] on their album ''[[All That Remains (album)|All That Remains]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=21910|title=FOZZY: Ex-MEGADETH Guitarist FRIEDMAN, CREED's TREMONTI To Guest On New CD |date=April 29, 2004|work=Blabbermouth.net|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070319022124/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=21910 |archivedate=March 19, 2007}}</ref> performing a guitar solo on the song \"The Way I Am\". His Alter Bridge band mate Myles Kennedy also appeared on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=29427|title=FOZZY: 'All That Remains' Track Listing, Artwork Revealed|date=November 20, 2004|work=Blabbermouth.net|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060421031113/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=29427|archivedate=April 21, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Tremonti made two guest appearances, one with the [[metalcore]] band [[Bury Your Dead]] on their [[Bury Your Dead (album)|self-titled album]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marktremonti.net/interview.php?id=mtnetmark|title=MarkTremonti.net interview with Mark Tremonti at the Croc Rock in Allentown, PA|date=July 25, 2008|publisher=MarkTremonti.net}}</ref> and another with [[Sevendust]] on the song \"Hope\" from ''[[Chapter VII: Hope & Sorrow]]'', which also featured appearances from Myles Kennedy and [[Chris Daughtry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=90338|title=SEVENDUST: New Song Posted Online|date=February 8, 2008|work=Blabbermouth.net|publisher=[[Roadrunner Records]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410211739/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=90338 |archivedate=April 10, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.melodic.net/?page=news&id=9779|title=New Sevendust Album To Feature Chris Daughtry, Mark Tremonti & Myles Kennedy|date=February 22, 2008|publisher=Melodic.net}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlthough Tremonti does not believe in organized religion or what is in the Bible, he does believe in his own version of God. On December 14, 2002, Tremonti married Victoria Rodriguez, with whom he has two sons, Austen and Pearson. They currently reside in Windermere, Florida.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nTremonti is a collector of [[guitar]]s, [[guitar amplifier|amplifiers]], and [[pinball]] machines, and is known to enjoy playing [[table tennis]].<ref name=\"imdb\"/> He is also an avid fan of reading: \"Five or six years ago,\" he told [[Artistdirect]], \"I started going crazy reading books. Now, I can't get enough.\" He has listed works such as the ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire|Song of Ice and Fire]]'' series by [[George R. R. Martin]], ''[[The Book of the New Sun]]'' by [[Gene Wolfe]], ''[[Old Man's War]]'' by [[John Scalzi]], ''[[The First Law]]'' trilogy by [[Joe Abercrombie]], ''[[The Prophet (book)|The Prophet]]'' by [[Khalil Gibran|Kahlil Gibran]], and ''[[On Writing: A Memoir of the Craft|On Writing]]'' by [[Stephen King]] as some of his favorites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/reading-list-mark-tremonti-of-alter-bridge-and-creed/9867380 |title=Reading List: Mark Tremonti of Alter Bridge and Creed |author=Rick Florino |publisher=[[Artistdirect]] |date=January 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOne of Tremonti's brothers, Michael, is Alter Bridge's fan liaison and publicist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espyrock.com/news/michael-tremonti-comments-on-recent-alter-bridge-rumours |title=Michael Tremonti comments on recent Alter Bridge rumors |publisher=EspyRock |date=July 20, 2010}}</ref> Another brother, Dan, has created the artwork for all of the albums by both Alter Bridge and Creed and is the president and creative director of a design/marketing company called Core Twelve.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.core12.com/ |title=CORE 12: A CREATIVE AGENCY|website=Core12.com|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> Tremonti's mother died in January 2002 and Alter Bridge's song \"In Loving Memory\" is a tribute to her.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/alter_bridge/artist.jhtml#biographyEnd |title=Alter Bridge - Full Biography |publisher=MTV|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and accolades==\n===RIAA certifications===\nThese statistics were compiled from the [[RIAA certification]] online database.<ref name=\"RIAA.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |title=Gold and Platinum database |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archivedate=2007-06-26 }}</ref>\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[My Own Prison]]'': 6\u00d7 platinum (August 2002)\n* ''[[Human Clay]]'': 11\u00d7 platinum, 1\u00d7(+) diamond (January 2004)\n* ''[[Weathered]]'': 6\u00d7 platinum (January 2003)\n* ''[[One Day Remains]]'': gold (November 2004)\n<!--Please do not include ''Full Circle'' on this list without a reliable source. The album is not in the RIAA database, so please do not include it until it has been officially confirmed.-->\n;Compilations\n* ''[[Greatest Hits (Creed album)|Greatest Hits]]'': 2\u00d7 platinum (November 2008)\n\n===Grammy Awards and nominations===\nThe [[Grammy Award]]s are awarded annually by the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]. With Creed, Mark Tremonti has been nominated for three Grammy Awards resulting in one win.<ref name=\"metrolyrics\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/creed-awards-featured.html |title=Awards for Creed |publisher=[[MetroLyrics]]|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n* \"[[With Arms Wide Open]]\" \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]], 2001 (nomination)<ref name=\"grammy\"/>\n* \"With Arms Wide Open\" \u2013 [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]], 2001 '''(winner)'''<ref name=\"grammy\"/>\n* \"[[My Sacrifice]]\" \u2013 Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal, 2003 (nomination)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/grammy/rockgroup.htm |title=GRAMMY AWARDS:BEST ROCK VOCAL PERFORMANCE BY A DUO OR GROUP |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other accolades===\n'''Loudwire Music Awards'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2013 || Mark Tremonti || Best Guitarist || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2015 || Mark Tremonti || Best Guitarist || {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n'''Metal Hammer Golden Gods Awards'''\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2008 || Mark Tremonti || Best Shredder || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2014 || Mark Tremonti || Riff Lord || {{won}}\n{{end}}\n\nTremonti was also named \"Guitarist of the Year\" for three consecutive years by ''[[Guitar World]]'' magazine,<ref name=\"prs\"/> and in 2011 he was listed as the fourth greatest [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] guitarist of all time by ''[[Total Guitar]]''.<ref name=\"totalguitar\"/> In addition, and also in 2011, the guitar solo in the [[Alter Bridge]] song \"[[Blackbird (Alter Bridge song)|Blackbird]],\" which Tremonti performed with [[Myles Kennedy]], was named the greatest guitar solo of all time by ''[[Guitarist (magazine)|Guitarist]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"greatest guitar solo\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n===Creed===\n{{Main|Creed discography}}\n;Studio albums\n*''[[My Own Prison]]'' (1997)\n*''[[Human Clay]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Weathered]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Full Circle (Creed album)|Full Circle]]'' (2009)\n;Compilation albums\n*''[[Greatest Hits (Creed album)|Greatest Hits]]'' (2004)\n*''[[With Arms Wide Open: A Retrospective]]'' (2015)\n\n===Alter Bridge===\n{{Main|Alter Bridge discography}}\n;Studio albums\n*''[[One Day Remains]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Blackbird (Alter Bridge album)|Blackbird]]'' (2007)\n*''[[AB III]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Fortress (Alter Bridge album)|Fortress]]'' (2013)\n*''[[The Last Hero (album)|The Last Hero]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Walk the Sky]] (2019)\n\n===Tremonti===\n{{Main|Mark Tremonti discography}}\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[All I Was]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Cauterize (album)|Cauterize]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Dust (Tremonti album)|Dust]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[A Dying Machine]]'' (2018)\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''Mark Tremonti: The Sound & the Story'' (2008)\n*''Alter Bridge: Fortress: The Sound & the Story'' (2014)\n*''OSW Review: Episode 84 - Survivor Series'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mark Tremonti}}\n* {{official website|http://www.marktremonti.com}}\n\n{{Tremonti}}\n{{Creed}}\n{{Alter Bridge}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tremonti, Mark}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Alter Bridge members]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Creed (band) members]]\n[[Category:Florida State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Roadrunner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Tremonti (band) members]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCreed:Add missing pipe)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Tremonti"}
{"title_page": "Jonas Kocher", "text_new": "{{short description|Swiss musician and composer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n\n'''Jonas Kocher''' is a musician and composer born in [[Nyon]] ([[Switzerland]]) in 1977. He is based in [[Biel/Bienne]] ([[Switzerland]]) since the late 1990s. \n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = \n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image = Acc jk 4.jpg\n| l\u00e9gende = Jonas Kocher 2014\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|08|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Nyon]], Switzerland\n| genre = [[Free improvisation]], [[experimental music]]\n| occupation = Musician, composer\n| instrument = Accordion\n| website = {{url|jonaskocher.net}}\n}}\n\n== Biography ==\nComposer and [[accordionist]], Jonas Kocher followed his musical studies at the University of the Arts in [[Bern]] between 1996 and 2004 with Teodoro Anzellotti, Pierre Sublet and [[Georges Aperghis]]. He soon developed a keen interest in experimental practices in sound and performance, which led him to explore musical theater as a performer in productions by [[:de:Ruedi H\u00e4usermann|Ruedy H\u00e4usermann]] and [[:de:Daniel Ott|Daniel Ott]] and electronic music in the BlindeKinder duo. Since 2003 he has been creating his own pieces of composed theatre, various sound performances and he also dedicates himself to composition and free improvisation. Starting from 2006 and for a few years, he has worked closely with Association Rue du Nord ([[Lausanne]]).\n\nSince 2008, he has performed as accordionist with regular partners such as [[:de:Jacques Demierre|Jacques Demierre]], [[:de:Axel D\u00f6rner|Axel D\u00f6rner]], [[:de: Joke Lanz|Joke Lanz]], Christian Wolfarth, Gaudenz Badrutt, [[:fr:Michel Doneda|Michel Doneda]], Chris Heenan, [[:de: Christof Kurzmann|Christof Kurzmann]], [[:pl:Alfredo Costa Monteiro|Alfredo Costa Monteiro]] (in the accordion trio 300 basses with [[:de:Luca Venitucci|Luca Venitucci]]), [[Leonel Kaplan]], [[:de:Hans Koch (Holzbl\u00e4ser)|Hans Koch]], [[Burkhard Beins]], [[Radu Malfatti]], [[Ilan Manouach]], [[:de:Andy Guhl|Andy Guhl]] and many others. His musical activity has led him to perform throughout Europe and in Russia, Japan and the USA and to collaborate with dancers and visual artists.\n\nAs interpreter, he encourages collaborations with musicians and composers such as Christian Kesten, Stefan Thut, [[Antoine Chessex]], Chiyoko Szlavnics or [[Radu Malfatti]]. If his practice of improvisation seems to contrast with his parallel interest in composition and sound performance, it is only because the creative dimension of these areas is not taken into account in its entirety; this is an area where Jonas Kocher sees a field of privileged artistic experimentation and where listening, sound and space are constantly explored.\n\nAs a composer, he has produced works that range between composed theatre, installations and concert pieces. He has composed occasionally for [[Radio drama|audio drama]], dance and theater. Jonas Kocher is active as an organizer of concerts in Switzerland and elsewhere and he is running BRUIT, a platform dedicated to experimental sound practices.\n\nIn 2005 he received the Art award of the city of [[Nyon]] and in 2010 the prize of recognition of the music committee of the [[Canton of Bern]]e. His works have been performed at the Biennale Bern 2010, Musikfestival Bern 2017 and 2018, Umlaut festival Berlin, the Jardins Musicaux festival of Cernier, the Forge London, the Zagreb Biennale, SMC Lausanne, Thessaloniki Art Biennale, etc.\n\n== Works ==\n* 2019: ''Perspectives and echoes'', for 6 players (percussion, live electronics and four instruments)\n* 2018: ''Avec Bataille'', performance for 7 participants with headphones and one improvising musician\n* 2018: ''HOME (M\u00fcnstergasse 37)'', in situ sound performance for 4 musicians and 2 actors\n* 2017: ''Irrlicht'', for loudspeakers and four performers in a resonant space\n* 2017: ''Rough'', for 10 musicians\n* 2015: ''h\u00e1los'', for harp solo\n* 2015: ''Intervention No. 2 [pasquart]'', in situ sound performance\n* 2015: ''Intervention No. 1 [cave12]'', in situ sound performance\n* 2013: ''Hornussen'', in situ sound performance\n* 2013: ''Nichi Nichi Kore Ko Nichi'', sound performance\n* 2012: ''Commedia'', for piano, clarinet, violin, vcello and pre-recorded sounds\n* 2011: ''Agitations (Adagio)'', for small symphony orchestra (young interpreters) and pre-recorded sounds\n* 2010: ''Frictions'', musical theater\n* 2010: ''Promenade \u00e0 travers une \u0153uvre'', in situ sound performance\n* 2010: ''Grrrrr!!'', for string quartet (young interpreters)\n* 2009: ''Serge'', for ensemble\n* 2008: ''3 ombres'', for ensemble (three compositions intended to be played with Pierrot Lunaire of A. Sch\u00f6nberg)\n* 2006: ''Vallon de l'Ermitage'', in situ sound performance\n* 2005: ''Dubbing & Naturjutz'', for ensemble\n* 2005: ''Harmonie mit schr\u00e4ger D\u00e4mpfung und Sopranbimbo'', for ensemble and pre-recorded sounds\n* 2004: ''Play Along'', for tenor saxophone and pre-recorded sounds\n* 2004: ''Kopf hoch!'' for 4 performers and 5 tape recorders\n* 2004: ''Les Adieux'', in situ sound performance / musical theater\n* 2003: ''Bianca K.'', musical theater\n\n== Discography ==\n* 2020 : ''Abstract Musette'' with Joke Lanz, LP/Corvo Records\n* 2018 : ''Cone of Confusion'' with Jacques Demierre and Axel D\u00f6rner, CD/BRUIT\n* 2017 : ''Spoon Bridge'', with Michel Doneda & Christian Wolfarth, digital download/Bandcamp\n* 2017 : ''Chiyoko Szlavnics \u2018During a Lifetime'', with Apartment House, Konus Quartet, Hannes Lingens, CD/Another Timbre\n* 2017 : ''HumaNoise Tutti '', with Erel, Kakaliagou, Marshall, Marwedel, Nabicht, Phillipp, Rodrigues, Schliemann, Souchal,  CD/Creative Sources\n* 2016 : ''Jonas Kocher plays Christian Kesten & Stefan Thut'', CD/BRUIT\n* 2016 : ''Floating piece of space'' with Jacques Demierre and Axel D\u00f6rner, LP/label cave12\n* 2016 : ''Kocher-Manouach-Papageorgiou'', CD/BRUIT\n* 2015 : ''Tria Atoma'', 300 Basses (Alfredo Costa Monteiro, Jonas Kocher et Luca Venitucci), CD/Moving Furniture Records\n* 2015 : ''Rotonda'' with Gaudenz Badrutt and Ilia Belorukov, CD/Intonema\n* 2015 : ''Koch-Kocher-Badrutt'' with Hans Koch and Gaudenz Badrutt, CD/BRUIT\n* 2015 : ''Skeleton Drafts'' with Ilan Manouach, CD/BRUIT-Romvos\n* 2014 : ''Cin\u00e9ma Rex'' with Gaudenz Badrutt, free download/Insubordination\n* 2013 : ''Le Belv\u00e9d\u00e8re du Rayon Vert'' with Michel Doneda, CD/Flexion records\n* 2013 : ''\u00d6cca'' with Jacques Demierre, Cyril Bondy and D'Incise, LP/Bocian records\n* 2012 : ''Sei Ritornelli'', 300 Basses (Alfredo Costa Monteiro, Jonas Kocher and Lucas Venitucci), CD/Potlatch\n* 2012 : ''Strategy of behaviour in unexpected situations'', with Gaudenz Badrutt, CD free download/Insubordination\n* 2012 : ''Duos 2011'' with H. Koch, P. Bosshard, G. Badrutt, C. Wolfarth, C. Schiller, U. Leimgruber, C. M\u00fcller, CD/Flexion records 2012\n* 2012 : ''archive #1'', with Insub meta orchestra, CD and free download/Insubordination\n* 2012 : ''D'Incise-Henning-Kocher-Sciss'', CD-r and free download/Insubordination\n* 2011 : ''Udarnik'' with Michel Doneda, Tomaz Grom and Tao G.V. Sambolec, CD/L'Innomable\n* 2011 : ''Action m\u00e9canique'' with Michel Doneda, CD/Flexion records\n* 2011 : ''Solo'', CD and free download/Insubordination\n* 2011 : ''///grape skin'' with Michel Doneda and Christophe Schiller, CD/Another Timbre\n* 2009 : ''Materials'', CD/Creative Sources\n* 2009 : ''Live at St-Gervais,'' Ensemble Rue du Nord, CD-r and free download/Insubordination\n* 2009 : ''M\u00fck\u00fcs'' with Morgane Gallay, Lionel Gafner, Lucien Dubuis, Vincent Membrez and Fred B\u00fcrki, CD/Veto records\n* 2009 : ''Blank Disc'' ''w/Jonas Kocher'' with Srdjan Muc and Robert Roza, CD-r\n* 2006 : ''BlindeKinder [helfen bauen]'' with Raphael Raccuia, CD/Everest records\n\n== References ==\n* [http://grisli.canalblog.com/archives/2016/05/01/33892617.html], Interview by Guillaume Belhomme in Le Son du grisli, 2016/02/06 (in French)\n* ''Revue & Corrig\u00e9e #97'' \u2013 Kasper T.Toeplitz /09/13, p.&nbsp;7-10\n* \"[http://dbserv1-bcu.unil.ch/persovd/composvdnom1.php?Num=5316 Jonas Kocher]\" in the [http://dbserv1-bcu.unil.ch/persovd/compositeursvd.php Vaudean Musicians] database\n* ''24 Heures'' \u2013 La C\u00f4te, 2005/12/12, p.&nbsp;20\n* [http://delarthelvetiquecontemporain.blog.24heures.ch/archive/2013/09/23/riches-heures-du-piano-du-pauvre-l-accordeon-electronique-de.html De l'art helv\u00e9tique contemporain], Blog 24 heures, Jean-Paul Gavard-Perret, 2013/23/09\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://jonaskocher.net/ Jonas Kocher website]\n* [http://www.bruit-asso.org/ BRUIT, sound and site specific activities]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kocher, Jonas}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Nyon]]\n[[Category:People from Biel/Bienne]]\n[[Category:Swiss composers]]\n[[Category:Swiss male composers]]\n[[Category:Swiss accordionists]]\n[[Category:21st-century accordionists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swiss musician and composer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n\n'''Jonas Kocher''' is a musician and composer born in [[Nyon]] ([[Switzerland]]) in 1977. He is based in [[Biel/Bienne]] ([[Switzerland]]) since the late 1990s. \n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = \n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image = Acc jk 4.jpg\n| l\u00e9gende = Jonas Kocher 2014\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|08|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Nyon]], Switzerland\n| genre = [[Free improvisation]], [[experimental music]]\n| occupation = Musician, composer\n| instrument = Accordion\n| website = {{url|jonaskocher.net}}\n}}\n\n== Biography ==\nComposer and [[accordionist]], Jonas Kocher followed his musical studies at the University of the Arts in [[Bern]] between 1996 and 2004 with Teodoro Anzellotti, Pierre Sublet and [[Georges Aperghis]]. He soon developed a keen interest in experimental practices in sound and performance, which led him to explore musical theater as a performer in productions by [[:de:Ruedi H\u00e4usermann|Ruedy H\u00e4usermann]] and [[:de:Daniel Ott|Daniel Ott]] and electronic music in the BlindeKinder duo. Since 2003 he has been creating his own pieces of composed theatre, various sound performances and he also dedicates himself to composition and free improvisation. Starting from 2006 and for a few years, he has worked closely with Association Rue du Nord ([[Lausanne]]).\n\nSince 2008, he has performed as accordionist with regular partners such as [[:de:Jacques Demierre|Jacques Demierre]], [[:de:Axel D\u00f6rner|Axel D\u00f6rner]], [[:de: Joke Lanz|Joke Lanz]], Christian Wolfarth, Gaudenz Badrutt, [[:fr:Michel Doneda|Michel Doneda]], Chris Heenan, [[:de: Christof Kurzmann|Christof Kurzmann]], [[:pl:Alfredo Costa Monteiro|Alfredo Costa Monteiro]] (in the accordion trio 300 basses with [[:de:Luca Venitucci|Luca Venitucci]]), [[Leonel Kaplan]], [[:de:Hans Koch (Holzbl\u00e4ser)|Hans Koch]], [[Burkhard Beins]], [[Radu Malfatti]], [[Ilan Manouach]], [[:de:Andy Guhl|Andy Guhl]] and many others. His musical activity has led him to perform throughout Europe and in Russia, Japan and the USA and to collaborate with dancers and visual artists.\n\nAs interpreter, he encourages collaborations with musicians and composers such as Christian Kesten, Stefan Thut, [[Antoine Chessex]], Chiyoko Szlavnics or [[Radu Malfatti]]. If his practice of improvisation seems to contrast with his parallel interest in composition and sound performance, it is only because the creative dimension of these areas is not taken into account in its entirety; this is an area where Jonas Kocher sees a field of privileged artistic experimentation and where listening, sound and space are constantly explored.\n\nAs a composer, he has produced works that range between composed theatre, installations and concert pieces. He has composed occasionally for [[Radio drama|audio drama]], dance and theater. Jonas Kocher is active as an organizer of concerts in Switzerland and elsewhere and he is running BRUIT, a platform dedicated to experimental sound practices.\n\nIn 2005 he received the Art award of the city of [[Nyon]] and in 2010 the prize of recognition of the music committee of the [[Canton of Bern]]e. His works have been performed at the Biennale Bern 2010, Musikfestival Bern 2017 and 2018, Umlaut festival Berlin, the Jardins Musicaux festival of Cernier, the Forge London, the Zagreb Biennale, SMC Lausanne, Thessaloniki Art Biennale, etc.\n\n== Works ==\n* 2019: ''Perspectives and echoes'', for 6 players (percussion, live electronics and four instruments)\n* 2018: ''Avec Bataille'', performance for 7 participants with headphones and one improvising musician\n* 2018: ''HOME (M\u00fcnstergasse 37)'', in situ sound performance for 4 musicians and 2 actors\n* 2017: ''Irrlicht'', for loudspeakers and four performers in a resonant space\n* 2017: ''Rough'', for 10 musicians\n* 2015: ''h\u00e1los'', for harp solo\n* 2015: ''Intervention No. 2 [pasquart]'', in situ sound performance\n* 2015: ''Intervention No. 1 [cave12]'', in situ sound performance\n* 2013: ''Hornussen'', in situ sound performance\n* 2013: ''Nichi Nichi Kore Ko Nichi'', sound performance\n* 2012: ''Commedia'', for piano, clarinet, violin, vcello and pre-recorded sounds\n* 2011: ''Agitations (Adagio)'', for small symphony orchestra (young interpreters) and pre-recorded sounds\n* 2010: ''Frictions'', musical theater\n* 2010: ''Promenade \u00e0 travers une \u0153uvre'', in situ sound performance\n* 2010: ''Grrrrr!!'', for string quartet (young interpreters)\n* 2009: ''Serge'', for ensemble\n* 2008: ''3 ombres'', for ensemble (three compositions intended to be played with Pierrot Lunaire of A. Sch\u00f6nberg)\n* 2006: ''Vallon de l'Ermitage'', in situ sound performance\n* 2005: ''Dubbing 